{Welcome, dear chess friends, to French According to Dreev – Part 2. In this course, we’ll provide a complete repertoire for Black against everything except 3.Nc3—which was thoroughly covered in Part 1, focused on the Armenian Variation.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 (2. d3 {Alexey takes a very practical approach against both 2.d3 and 2.Qe2. His main philosophy is to avoid mainstream theory and instead go for something solid, easy to learn, and effective over the board.}) (2. Nf3 {and White's other 2nd-move rare options will be analyzed in the "Extra" section.}) 2... d5 3. e5 {The Advance Variation is extremely important, as White immediately grabs space — and if Black isn’t well-prepared, it’s easy to end up in a passive position for a long time.} ({Against the Exchange French} 3. exd5 exd5 4. Nf3 {Alexey's recommendation is} Nf6 5. Bd3 c5 $5 {[%csl Bc5] Following the footsteps of the recent World Championship game Gukesh–Ding, 2024.}) (3. Nd2 {The Tarrasch Variation is often annoying for French players to face, as White typically aims for an extremely solid setup and tries to keep the game in a 2-result zone. Our recommendation against it is} c5 {We will analyze this line in Chapters 1, 2, and 3—not only from a theoretical point of view, but also with a strong focus on practical aspects.} 4. exd5 {White's mainline.} (4. Ngf3 cxd4 5. Nxd4 {now our recommendation will be} Nf6 $5 {[%csl Bf6]}) 4... Qxd5 5. Ngf3 cxd4 6. Bc4 {In this critical position, our recommendation will be} Qd7 $5 {[%csl Cd7] and it will be investigated in Chapters 2 and 3.}) 3... c5 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. c3 Bd7 {[%csl Bd7] Alexey's recommendation, and we will cover these lines in Chapters 4-8. The two most important directions are} (5... Qb6 {was Jobava's recommendation.}) 6. Be2 (6. a3 c4 {[%csl Bc4][%cal Cf7f6] as we will see in Chapter 6, our idea is to continue with f6 against almost every White's move.}) 6... f6 $5 {[%csl Bf6] This is how Dreev likes to handle the position: he aims to clarify the center immediately and reach a fighting setup, where he can play for a win without relying on heavy memorization.} *

