1. e4 {t} e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 {[%csl Bc5] This is Black's most principled variation against the Tarrasch.} 4. Ngf3 {White's second most important move.} (4. exd5 {will be analyzed in Chapters 2 and 3.}) (4. c3 {t} cxd4 5. cxd4 dxe4 6. Nxe4 Nf6 $36 {[%csl Rd4] Black has some initiative and easy play.}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 {[%csl Bf6] My recommendation.} (5... Nc6 {is Black's mainline, but after} 6. Bb5 Bd7 {there is a big theory, and White's position is very risk-free.}) 6. exd5 {The main line.} (6. e5 {t This is more serious and it is the main alternative to 6.exd5.} Nfd7 7. N2f3 {Necessary.} (7. f4 $2 {t} Nxe5 $1 $17 {[%csl Rd4,Re1][%cal Rf4e5,Gd8h4] Taking on e5 is impossible, because of Qh4+.}) 7... Nc6 8. Bf4 {The only logical move.} (8. Nxc6 $6 {t Common positional mistake.} bxc6 {[%csl Gc6,Gd5] The structure is improved for Black.} 9. Bd3 {is met with:} Ba6 $1 $15 {[%csl Ga6][%cal Rd3a6,Gd8a5] Typical tactical idea, and Black has a dream position.}) 8... Qb6 {[%csl Bb6] I think this is easier.} (8... Be7 $5 {Possible alternative.} 9. c3 {is met with:} (9. h4 $5 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Gh4g5] White stops g5.} Qb6 10. Rb1 O-O 11. Bd3 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gd3h7] White is ready for some sacrifices, that's why Black should play:} Nxd4 12. Nxd4 h6 $1 {[%csl Bh6] Good prophylactic move.} (12... f6 {also a good move, the problem is that it allows a draw by repetition:} 13. Qh5 h6 14. Qg6 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 fxe5 16. Qh7+ $11 {[%cal Gh7g6,Gg6h7] Equal.} Kf7 17. Bg6+ $5 {If White decides to play for a win, it's very double edged:} Kf6 18. Rh3 e4 $1 {To stop Rf3.} 19. Rd1 Bc5 $13 {[%csl Gc5] Unclear position, but I prefer Black. It's tough to coordinate the attack.}) 13. O-O f6 $1 {[%csl Gf6,Rh4] We open the center, and White's also risking here a bit:} 14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Be3 $1 {[%csl Ge3] Best move.} e5 16. Nf5 Qc7 17. c3 Nb6 18. Qh5 e4 $36 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4,Rh4] Black has some initiative thanks to the center, and long term weakness of the h4 pawn.}) 9... g5 $1 {[%csl Re5,Be7,Bg5] Standard positional idea.} 10. Nxg5 $1 {[%csl Bg5][%cal Rc6d4,Gg5f7] This is White's best, to enter the complications.} (10. Bg3 $6 {slow move.} Qb6 $1 $146 {[%csl Bb6] The best option.} (10... h5 $5 {deserves attention.}) 11. Rb1 h5 $15 {[%csl Rd4,Rg3] White is running big strategical risks.}) 10... Nxd4 $1 {We can follow the game Milov-Tiviakov, Leiden op 2015.} (10... Bxg5 $2 {Don't fall for the trap.} 11. Nxe6 $3 $18 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Rf7e6,Gd1h5] We can't capture the knight.}) 11. Nxf7 $1 {[%csl Gf7] White's idea.} Nc2+ $5 {Before capturing, Tiviakov included this useful intermezzo.} (11... Kxf7 {possible way.} 12. Qh5+ Kg8 13. cxd4 $5 {The position is quite interesting, according to engine, White has full compensation.} (13. Qg4+ $11 {[%cal Gg4h5,Gg8f7] White can also force a draw.}) 13... Qf8 $1 $146 {[%csl Gf8][%cal Gf8f7] Best move, to activate the queen.} 14. Bh6 Qf7 15. Qh3 Qf5 {We follow the queen.} 16. Qg3+ Qg6 17. Bd3 $1 {But without preparation, it's quite difficult to play with White:} Qxg3 18. fxg3 $1 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gh1f1] To open the f-file for the attack.} (18. hxg3 $2 {Mistake.} Nb8 $1 $17 {[%cal Gb8c6] Black is better.}) 18... Bf8 {The line continues with:} 19. Bg5 h6 20. Bh4 Nb8 21. O-O Bd7 $13 {[%cal Rf1f4,Gh6h5] Strange position, balanced according to the engine.}) 12. Kd2 $1 {The best.} (12. Qxc2 $2 {Mistake.} Kxf7 $1 $15 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Rd1h5] There is no Qh5+.}) 12... Kxf7 {The simplest.} (12... Qb6 $5 $13 {was played in the game, but it was very double-edged.}) 13. Qh5+ Kg8 {White can secure the draw, or try to play on:} 14. Bd3 $5 Nxa1 15. h4 {[%cal Gh1h3,Gh3g3] One rook and 2 knights is the material disadvantage for White, but mate is a serious threat:} Nf6 $1 {[%cal Ge7f6,Yg8f8,Yf8e7,Ye7d7] The best, to organize an escape route for the king on g8.} 16. exf6 Bxf6 17. Bh6 $1 {[%csl Rg8] Only move to stop the king.} (17. Rh3 $2 {Mistake.} Kf8 $1 $19 {[%cal Gf8e7] Black wins.}) 17... e5 18. Re1 {[%cal Ge1e3,Ge3g3] The rook tries to get to g3 in another way, but it's maximum a draw:} e4 19. Re3 Bxh4 $1 {[%csl Rg3] To control the square.} 20. Qe5 Bf6 21. Qh5 $11 {Draw.}) 9. Rb1 {Main move.} (9. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1] t White gives up the pawn for development:} Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Qxb2 11. O-O Qc3 $5 {We are following one email game:} 12. Nb5 Qc6 13. c4 $1 {[%csl Gc4] s White's only try.} dxc4 14. Rb1 a6 {The position is unclear, but balanced:} 15. Bf3 Qc5 16. Nd6+ Bxd6 17. exd6 O-O $11 {White has compensation, but maximum for equality.}) 9... Bc5 {[%csl Gb6,Gc5,Rf2][%cal Gc5f2] Black can switch to active play.} 10. c3 f6 $1 {[%csl Bf6][%cal Rd4e6,Gc5f2] Key point.} 11. exf6 {Tried in 3 email games.} (11. b4 {t} Nxd4 $1 {[%cal Rb4c5,Gd4f3] Good intermezzo.} 12. Nxd4 Be7 13. exf6 Bxf6 {s} 14. Be3 O-O 15. Be2 Ne5 16. O-O Bd7 $11 {Black had no problems and went on to win the game.}) 11... O-O $5 $146 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gf8f4] Possible novelty, using the pin.} (11... Nxf6 $11 {Good enough.}) 12. b4 Bxd4 $1 {[%cal Rf3d4,Ge6e5] s} 13. cxd4 Nxf6 {[%cal Gf6e4] White has two bishops, but the position is concrete, Ne4 is a big threat.} 14. Bd3 Ne4 15. Be3 {White has to sacrifice the exchange:} Nc3 16. Bxh7+ $1 {[%cal Rg8h7,Gf3g5] Tactical point.} Kh8 $1 17. Qd2 $1 Nxb1 18. Bxb1 Qxb4 $44 {Maximum White has compensation for equality, but not more than that.}) (6. Bb5+ {t} Bd7 {The simplest.} 7. exd5 (7. Bxd7+ {t} Nbxd7 8. exd5 Nxd5 $11 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] There are some games, but the position is equal and playble.} (8... Ne5 $5 $11 {[%cal Gd8d5] deserves attention, to take on d5 with the queen.})) 7... Bxb5 8. Nxb5 a6 $5 {[%csl Ga6] Useful inclusion.} 9. Nc3 Nxd5 $11 {Equal chances.}) (6. Bd3 $6 {t} e5 $1 {[%csl Be5] Best move.} 7. N4f3 dxe4 $1 {The following endgame is unpleasant for White:} 8. Nxe4 Nxe4 9. Bxe4 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 f6 $15 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gb8c6,Gb8a6] The knight on f3 is misplaced.}) 6... Nxd5 $5 {Other moves are also good.} (6... Qxd5 {also possible.} 7. Nb5 $5 {The only interesting try.} (7. N2f3 {Harmless line.} Nc6 8. Nxc6 (8. Be2 {leads to an endgame:} Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Qxd4 10. Nxd4 Bd7 $11 {Just equal.}) 8... Qxd1+ $5 {We are not afraid of this endgame:} 9. Kxd1 bxc6 10. Bd3 Bd6 {Let's see how it can develop.} 11. c3 c5 12. Nd2 Bb7 13. Nc4 Bc7 14. f3 h5 $5 {Normal inclusion.} 15. h4 Nd5 16. Kc2 Ke7 17. Bd2 Rad8 18. Be1 Nf4 19. Bf1 Rd5 $1 {[%csl Gb7,Gc7,Gd5,Gf4] Black has very good pieces.} 20. Bf2 Rhd8 $11 {Equal endgame.}) (7. Nc4 {Very rare move.} Bc5 8. Be3 O-O $36 {[%csl Rc4,Rd4,Re3][%cal Gf8d8] White has to be a bit careful, the pieces are strange.}) 7... Qd8 $1 {[%csl Bd8] The easiest move, played in MVL-Caruana, 0-1, Paris 2017.} 8. Nc4 $1 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gb5d6] The best.} (8. Bd3 $6 {was White's choice, but it was unfortunate:} a6 $1 9. Nc3 Nc6 10. O-O Ne5 $1 $36 {[%csl Rd3,Ge5][%cal Ge5d3,Yd3e2,Gd8c7] Caruana seized the initiative.}) 8... Nd5 $1 {And it leads to a position with isolated pawn:} 9. Ne3 {The only try.} (9. Be2 {Harmless.} Nc6 10. O-O Bc5 $11 {[%cal Ga7a6]}) 9... a6 $1 {[%csl Ba6] Key move.} 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Nd4 {[%csl Gd4] looks pleasant for White, but in reality it's nothing:} Nc6 12. Be3 (12. Be2 Bc5 13. Be3 Qf6 $11 {[%csl Rd4] Black loses control of the d4 square.}) 12... Bd6 $1 {[%csl Bd6] The best.} 13. Be2 O-O 14. O-O Qc7 $1 {[%csl Bc7,Rh2][%cal Bd6h2] Clean equalizer:} 15. h3 Bh2+ 16. Kh1 Bf4 $1 $11 {[%csl Bf4] A lot of minor pieces come off the board, and the arising position is just equal.}) 7. N2f3 {Most logical.} (7. c3 {t Harmless.} Bc5 $5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gc5d4] Rare option, but very good.} 8. Ne4 Bxd4 {is the idea, there is no need to worry about losing the bishop.} 9. Qxd4 O-O {[%cal Gb8c6,Gf7f5,Ye6e5] Black has many developing moves with tempo.} 10. Be2 f5 $1 {Good move, played by GM Boruchovsky.} 11. Ng5 Nc6 12. Qc5 $1 $146 {[%csl Gc5] The best square for the queen, but quite difficult to understand.} (12. Qh4 $6 {Not great.} h6 $15 {[%cal Gd8h4] Black was slightly better in Sokolovsky-Boruchovsky, 0-1, ISR-ch 2022.}) (12. Qd1 $6 {also too slow.} h6 $1 13. Nf3 e5 $1 $15 {[%csl Gc6,Gd5,Be5,Bf5] This is Black's idea behind ...f5, we are just better.}) 12... h6 {s} 13. Nf3 Qc7 $132 {[%cal Gb7b6] Next move is b6, with an equal playable position.}) 7... Bb4+ $1 {Known equalizer.} 8. Bd2 {Necessary.} (8. c3 $2 {t} Nxc3 $1 $17 {[%cal Rb2c3,Gb4c3,Yc1d2,Yc3d4] And White just loses a pawn.}) 8... O-O 9. Bxb4 {Main.} (9. c3 {t} Bd6 $11 {[%csl Rd2] The bishop is misplaced.}) (9. Bc4 {t} Bc5 $5 {[%csl Bc5] The easiest.} (9... e5 $1 $11 {[%cal Rf3e5,Gf8e8] at}) 10. c3 (10. Nb3 Be7 $36 {[%csl Rb3,Rd2][%cal Ge7f6,Gb7b6,Gc8b7] All the pieces are strange.}) 10... b6 $11 {[%cal Gc8b7] There are 3 games of Grischuk, but in general, Black doesn't experience any problem.}) 9... Nxb4 10. c3 N4c6 {[%cal Gc6d4] The most simple, just exchange everything.} 11. Bc4 Bd7 $5 $146 {Good development.} 12. O-O Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Nc6 14. Nf3 Qc7 $11 {[%cal Gf8d8,Ga8c8] No need to analyze, Black has no problems.} *

