1. e4 {t} e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 Qxd5 {This is our main recommendation.} (4... exd5 {is also a good option from the objective point of view.} 5. Ngf3 Nf6 6. Bb5+ {The line usually continues with:} Bd7 7. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 8. O-O Be7 9. dxc5 Nxc5 10. Nb3 Nce4 $11 {The position is equal, but it's not a position suitable for all players, Black has to play with an isolated pawn, but if you don't mind it, then you can play 4...exd5 as well.}) 5. Ngf3 {The main line by far.} (5. dxc5 {t Second option, way less played than 5.Ngf3, the idea is to finish devlopment and play a balanced position. It's a harmless line for today's standard.} Nf6 {[%cal Gd5c5] We recommend to capture on c5 without allowing Ne4, but of course, taking immediately is also fine.} (5... Qxc5 {Possible move order.} 6. Ne4 $5 {Extra line.} (6. Ngf3 Nf6 {transposes.}) 6... Qb4+ (6... Qc7 $5 $11 {also possible, there are a few high-level games, but Black should be okay.}) 7. Nc3 {[%csl Rb4] Qb4 can be misplaced.} Nf6 {For the engine, this is fine.} 8. a3 Qa5 9. Bd3 a6 10. Bf4 {This is how the game Karjakin-Giri, 1-0, Tata Steel-A 2012 continued, Black is fine with many moves.} e5 $5 $146 {deserved attention.} (10... Nbd7 $11 {Giri's move was fine as well.})) 6. Ngf3 {The main move.} (6. Nb3 {t White's extra option, but it's a bit risky.} Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 Nbd7 {[%csl Rd1][%cal Gd7c5] If Black manages to regain material balance, White is the one fighting for equality, since the king is in the center.} 8. Bb5 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gb5e8] That's why, White should pin the knight.} a6 9. Ba4 Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] Black wants to castle.} 10. Nf3 {Most logical move.} (10. f3 $2 {[%cal Rc1e3,Re3f2] t was played in a recent game Aronian-Nakamura, 0-1, Saint Louis Blitz 2024. It's too slow.} O-O 11. Be3 Nd5 $1 {[%csl Rd1][%cal Gf8d8] White is already in trouble.} 12. Bd4 Rd8 $1 $146 {[%csl Bd8] Improvement over the game, introducing a fancy idea:} 13. Ne2 N7b6 $3 {[%csl Bb6][%cal Rb6a4] s Key move, the bishop is trapped.} 14. cxb6 Nxb6 $17 {[%csl Ra4,Rd1][%cal Gd8d1] Black is much better.}) 10... O-O 11. Be3 Nd5 $1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd5e3] Good tempo against the bishop.} 12. Bd4 Rd8 13. Ke2 Nf4+ $1 {[%csl Bf4] Simple intermezzo.} (13... f6 $6 {In the game Bruzon-Lomasov, Pan American 2025, Black tried this logical move, but it's a bit slow:} 14. Rhd1 $1 {[%csl Gd1][%cal Gd1d8] White is in time to develop the rook.} e5 15. Be3 Nxe3 16. fxe3 $1 $14 {White was slightly better.}) 14. Kf1 f6 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Rh1d1] s Compared to the Lomasov game, now the rook on h1 is stuck.} 15. c4 {The critical move, to control the d5 square.} (15. g3 {is met with:} e5 $1 {[%csl Be5] Good intermezzo, and Black is doing great:} 16. gxf4 exd4 $11 {[%csl Rc5] c5 falls, with full compensation.}) 15... e5 16. Be3 Ne6 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gd7c5] To target the c5 pawn.} (16... Nd3 {also possible, and most likely will lead to the same.} 17. c6 N7c5 18. Nxc5 Nxc5 {transposition.}) 17. c6 $1 {The critical try.} (17. Rd1 {[%csl Gd1,Rd8] White defends it tactically.} Rb8 $1 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gb7b5] Good move, b5 is a very serious idea.} 18. Ke2 $1 {[%csl Ge2] The best move, to bring the other rook into the game.} (18. g3 $2 {Just to highlight the risk White is running:} b5 $3 {[%csl Bb5] Key move and White is in deep trouble.} 19. cxb6 Nxb6 20. Rxd8+ Nxd8 21. Bxb6 Rxb6 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Gb6b4] Rb4 is not easy to defend against.} 22. a3 Bd7 $3 {[%csl Ra4,Rb3,Bd7] Final touch.} 23. Bxd7 Rxb3 $17 {[%csl Ra3,Rb2] From a pawn up endgame, White will need to defend a hard pawn down endgame.}) 18... b5 $1 {We go for the same reaction.} 19. cxb6 Nxb6 20. Rxd8+ Bxd8 $5 {[%csl Gd8][%cal Gd8b6] This time we can recapture with the bishop.} (20... Nxd8 {Going for the same line is less appealing:} 21. Bxb6 Rxb6 22. Rd1 $5 {[%csl Gd1] Probably easier, and this is a key point.} (22. a3 $6 Bd7 23. Bxd7 Rxb3 24. Rb1 $15 {The endgame is holdable after Bxa3.}) 22... Rb4 23. Bd7 $1 $11 {[%csl Gd7] Equal endgame.}) 21. Bc6 (21. Bxb6 Nf4+ $15 {[%csl Re2][%cal Gd8b6] Bxb6 next and Black is slightly better.}) 21... Nxc4 $15 {[%cal Gc4e3] Capture the bishop on e3 next, and it's only Black who can fight for the full point.}) 17... Ndc5 $1 {[%csl Ra4] Good tempo.} 18. Nxc5 Nxc5 19. cxb7 Bxb7 {[%csl Gb7,Gc5,Ge7,Rf1] White has a clear extra pawn, but Black has full compensation thanks to the piece coordination and poor king placement.} 20. Bc2 Rab8 21. b3 Ne6 {[%csl Ge5,Gf6][%cal Ge5e4,Gf6f5] Actually, White is the one risking, because the pawns will become mobile, for example:} 22. Ke2 e4 $1 {[%csl Rf3] The knight doesn't have a good square.} 23. Nh4 $1 {[%csl Gh4][%cal Gh4f5] Necessary move.} (23. Nd2 $2 {Logical, but it loses!} f5 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gf5f4]} 24. g3 g5 $17 {[%cal Gf5f4] f4 is a big threat, a human is losing this with White 100%.}) 23... g6 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Gf6f5] Good move, to prepare f5.} 24. g3 f5 25. Ng2 $1 {[%csl Gg2] This White's idea, the knight is a strong defending piece.} Nd4+ {[%csl Bd4] Still, Black is never running any risk:} 26. Bxd4 Rxd4 27. Rhd1 Rxd1 28. Rxd1 Kf7 29. Nf4 Bc6 30. Nd5 Bc5 $44 {[%csl Bc5,Bc6][%cal Ba6a5,Ba5a4,Gh7h5] Full compensation, the bishops are in full control, it's impossible for White to create progress with the queenside pawns.}) 6... Qxc5 7. Bd3 {[%cal Gd1e2,Ge1g1,Gd2e4] This is White's plan, but of course, not too serious from a theoretical perspective.} (7. Nb3 $6 {t} Qc7 $15 {[%csl Rb3] Nb3 is misplaced.}) 7... Nbd7 8. O-O Qc7 $1 {[%csl Cc7,Rd3][%cal Gd7c5] Black is ready for Nc5.} 9. Re1 {[%csl Ge1] This has a slight idea, but of course, it's also not too scary.} (9. Qe2 {t White usually plays this move, but it's not challenging at all.} Nc5 10. Bb5+ {Most common move.} (10. Bc4 {[%csl Rc4] t The bishop is just not a great piece here.} Bd6 11. b3 O-O 12. Bb2 b6 $15 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ga8d8] The engine rightfully prefers Black already, this is a dream setup.}) 10... Bd7 11. Ne5 {was tried in the game Petenyi-Bluebaum, EU-chT 2021.} (11. Bxd7+ {t White usually takes, and the position is just equal:} Ncxd7 12. Ne4 Be7 $11 {4 draws and 1 win for Black, so we are just very comfortable.}) 11... Bxb5 12. Qxb5+ Ncd7 13. Nxd7 Qxd7 14. Qxd7+ Nxd7 $36 {Engine sligthly gives a plus, so we can say that Black is on the comfortable side of equality.}) (9. a4 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Ga4a5,Rb7b6] t Prophylaxis move against b6.} Be7 {We can finish development, anyway we are not in a hurry to improve the c8 bishop.} (9... b6 $6 {is met with:} 10. a5 $1 $14 {[%csl Ga5]}) 10. a5 Nc5 {[%csl Gc5,Rd3] To harass the bishop.} 11. Bc4 O-O 12. Qe2 {[%cal Gb2b4,Rc5e4] White stops Ne4.} (12. b4 $6 {t} Nce4 $15 {[%csl Rb4,Rc3,Be4] Black is just slightly better.}) 12... a6 13. Re1 {Logical plan.} (13. b4 $6 {t is still too early.} Ncd7 $15 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gb7b5] b4 is just a long term weakness.}) 13... b5 $1 {[%csl Bb5] Good reaction, we copy some ideas from the Sicilian as well.} 14. axb6 Qxb6 $132 {[%cal Gc8b7] Position is playable, for 3 results, Black has a comfortable setup.}) (9. Nb3 $6 {[%csl Rb3] t stops Nc5, but the knight isn't a great piece here.} b6 10. a4 a6 $1 {[%csl Ga6][%cal Ra4a5,Gb6b5] Good prophylactic move.} (10... Bb7 $6 {allows:} 11. a5 $1 $132 {[%csl Ga5] With some unnecessary tension.}) 11. Qe2 Bb7 $15 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gf8d6,Ge8g8] Black was slightly better in Bjerre-Salem, 0-1, Biel GM Rapid 2024.}) 9... Be7 {Normal development.} (9... Nc5 $6 {No need to rush with this move.} 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Bf1 $1 $14 {[%csl Rd7,Bf1][%cal Gf3e5] This is White's point, and okay, White can argue and hope for some slight advantage.}) 10. Ne4 O-O 11. Nxf6+ Nxf6 $11 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] The position is equal, playable for both sides, you can go also deeper, if you are not familiar with the structure, but in general, the position is simple to play: b6-Bb7 next, rooks in the center, and watch out for any Nxf7 tricks and you should be fine.}) 5... cxd4 6. Bc4 {[%cal Gd5d6,Gd5d7,Gd5d8] The main line, and theory splits at this point, because all 3 retreating squares are good for Black.} (6. Nb3 $6 {t is a mistake.} e5 $1 $15 {[%cal Gb8c6,Rc2c3,Gc8g4] c3 is met with Nc6-Bg4, but it is fairly known that White shouldn't enter this position. Black is just slightly better.}) (6. g3 $5 {[%csl Gg3] t This is quite often played by GM Safarli, he also likes to play a similar system with g3 in the Delayed Alapin with e6.} Nf6 {This is the simplest way to handle the position.} (6... Nc6 {was played in Safarli-Pragg, 1-0, Wch Rapid New York 2024.} 7. Bg2 Qb5 $1 {[%csl Bb5][%cal Re1g1] Another good way.} 8. a4 Qa6 9. Bf1 {White aims for a repetition of moves.} Qa5 10. Bg2 Qa6 $11 (10... e5 $5 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gc2c3] Pragg decided to play on, but GM Safarli managed to create some chaotic gambit-style play and later won.})) 7. Bg2 b6 $1 {[%csl Bb6][%cal Gc8b7] Key move. Maybe people are afraid to play this, or just don't know it exists, but this solves all problems in a simple fashion.} 8. O-O Bb7 9. Nb3 {Sample line of how the game could continue:} d3 $1 {[%csl Gd3] Good reaction, to make it harder to recapture the pawn.} 10. c3 Be7 11. Nbd4 O-O {By the time White restores material balance, Black is fully mobilized.} 12. Bf4 Qc5 13. Qxd3 Nbd7 14. Rfe1 Rad8 $132 {[%cal Gc5c8,Gd7c5,Ga7a6] Just a normal position, playable. Black has no problems, and has easy moves next.}) 6... Qd7 {[%csl Bd7] I like this square, it is the second move by popularity, so maybe your opponents will be less prepared to face it.} 7. O-O {The main move.} (7. Nb3 $6 {t} Qc7 $1 {[%csl Rc4] Good intermezzo, and the bishop is exposed.} 8. Qxd4 {White captures with the queen, but it's not so pleasant since it runs into another tempo:} (8. Qe2 {t White's natural reply, but it is met with:} Bb4+ $1 {[%csl Bb4,Re1] Using the fact that White didn't castle in time.} 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Nbxd2 Nc6 {[%csl Gc6] s And once again, White will restore material balance, but Black has all the time in the world to organize the pieces.} 11. Nb3 a6 12. Nbxd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Nf6 14. O-O b5 $11 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ge8g8] The bishop will be very strong on b7, and we are happy to have exchanged more pieces, nothing can bother us on the kingside.}) 8... Nc6 9. Qh4 Be7 {[%csl Ge7] s Another tempo.} 10. Qg3 $146 {The best.} (10. Bg5 {t} Ne5 $1 $36 {[%csl Be5] Strong move, with some initiative already.}) 10... Qxg3 11. hxg3 Nf6 $132 {[%eval -10,0] for the engine, so Black is again quite comfortable.}) 7... Nc6 8. Nb3 a6 $1 {[%csl Ba6] This is a good move to include, since anyway it is useful for us.} 9. Nbxd4 {The main line.} (9. Re1 {t Strange move, because it allows:} Bb4 $1 {[%csl Bb4] Tempo and we will exchange the bishops.} 10. Bd2 Bxd2 11. Qxd2 Nf6 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Easy moves next.}) (9. a4 {t The second important line. White stops b5.} Nf6 {[%csl Ya4,Ga6] And we are happy to provoke a4, it's not a harmful move for White, but also not the most useful.} 10. Qe2 $5 Bd6 11. Rd1 {[%csl Gd1] This is White's idea, to first develop the pieces before capturing on d4.} O-O 12. Nbxd4 e5 $1 {[%csl Be5] Key move to remember.} 13. Nxc6 Qxc6 {[%cal Ge5e4,Gc8g4] We want to get counterplay in the center.} 14. Bg5 Bc7 $1 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gc6f6] To protect the f6 knight.} 15. Bxf6 {The main try, positionally it makes some sense, but at the same time, it maximum achieves equality for White:} (15. Ra3 {[%csl Ga3][%cal Ga3g3] This is maybe the most active try, White wants to swing the rook.} e4 16. Nd4 Qd6 $1 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gd6h2] Threaten mate.} 17. Rg3 Qc5 $1 {[%csl Bc5,Rg3][%cal Gc7g3] Key idea, to attack the rook.} (17... Qe7 $6 {Don't play this immediately.} 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 19. Re3 $14 {[%csl Re4] The pawn drops, White is better.}) 18. Nb3 {The best.} Qe7 19. Bxf6 Qxf6 $36 {[%csl Rb3] But to have a knight on b3 is a clear improvemet for Black.} 20. Re3 Bf5 $36 {[%csl Oe4][%cal Gf5g6] The pawn is quite solid, and also b2 is hanging, so White has to be careful.}) (15. h3 $5 {[%csl Gh3] White preemptively secures the g4 square against the bishop.} e4 16. Nd2 h6 {We can follow the game Lagunow-Gavrilescu, 2020. GM Gavrilescu is a young player with good theoretical knowledge of the French.} 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 {[%csl Rb2] b2 is a weakness.} 18. Qxe4 {The game developed naturally:} (18. Nxe4 Qxb2 $11 {Position is just equal.}) (18. c3 $6 {too slow.} Qe5 $1 $15 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Ge5h2] Nf1 is the best, but okay, it's too passive.}) 18... Qxb2 19. Bd5 Qe5 20. Qxe5 Bxe5 {And obviously, the pair of bishops compensate the weakness of the b7 pawn.} 21. Rab1 Rb8 22. Nc4 Bc7 {[%cal Rd5f3,Gb7b5] In the game, White allowed b5, which is of course, what David wanted.} 23. a5 Rd8 $11 {[%csl Ga5,Rb7][%cal Gg8f8,Gh6h5,Yc8f5] Even if White did everything correctly, it is still just equal, because no further way to improve the position, and 3 good moves in a row from Black, and let's say 1-2 from White, and the situation can turn around.}) 15... Qxf6 16. Bd5 {[%csl Gd5] The bishop is active, but Black can play around it:} g6 $5 {[%cal Gg8g7] s Black can just improve the position slowly.} 17. Ra3 {was tried in Bilguun-Baenziger, Arona op 2024.} (17. Qc4 Qe7 18. Ng5 Bb6 $132 {[%csl Rg5] The knight is misplaced, tactics are not working.}) 17... Kg7 18. Re3 Re8 $11 {[%cal Ga8b8] Black doesn't have any problems and soon players agreed to a draw.}) 9... Nxd4 10. Nxd4 {The main move.} (10. Qxd4 {t There are around 150 games in this endgame, but it's nothing special for White.} Qxd4 11. Nxd4 Bd7 $1 {[%cal Ga8c8] Good move, no need to expose ourselves with b5.} 12. Be2 {[%cal Ge2f3] White's main try to reroute the bishop.} (12. Bf4 {t was played by GM Li.} Rc8 13. Be2 Bc5 $11 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge7c6,Ge7g6,Ge8e7,Ge8g8] Black was just fine in Li-Xu, Chinese National Championship 2021.}) 12... Bd6 13. Rd1 (13. Bf3 {t} O-O-O $11 {Equal endgame, I would say that Black is even on the better side of equality.}) 13... O-O-O $11 {Black is doing fine, we can check the game that reached this position.} 14. Bf3 Ne7 15. Be3 e5 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gd7c6] s Good decision, to free up some space for the pieces.} 16. Nb3 Bc6 17. Bxc6 Nxc6 18. Bb6 Bc7 $1 {Black was slowly outplaying, the evaluation continues to grow:} 19. Bxc7 Kxc7 20. c3 Rxd1+ 21. Rxd1 Rd8 22. Rxd8 Nxd8 23. h4 Ne6 $36 {[%cal Gf7f5,Ge5e4] Players agreed to a draw in Cumming-Del Rio de Angelis, Portuguese Team Championship 2024. But the engine slightly prefers Black, and I have seen many times that these endgames end in a win for Black, because the pawn majority is more flexible, and the pieces are more active.}) 10... Qc7 {This is the starting critical position of the Tarrasch, and we will speak about it in the next Chapter.} *

