1. e4 {t} e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Ngf3 cxd4 6. Bc4 Qd7 7. O-O Nc6 8. Nb3 a6 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Qc7 {[%csl Bc7][%cal Rc7c4] Optimal square for the queen and White now has to either move or defend the bishop.} 11. Bb3 {White's most common move.} (11. Be2 {[%cal Ge2f3] t} Bd6 {[%cal Rd6h2]} 12. h3 (12. g3 {[%cal Ge2f3] t} e5 $1 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Re5d4] Taking the center and chasing the knight.} 13. Nb3 {[%csl Gf3] To keep the f3 square for the bishop.} Ne7 {[%cal Ge8g8] Completing development.} 14. Bf3 O-O $15 {With an equal position and easy play for Black.}) 12... Ne7 {[%csl Be7] Most flexible square for the knight.} 13. c4 {[%cal Rc4b5] Stopping b5 and gaining space.} O-O 14. Be3 h6 $11 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gb7b6,Gc8b7] Prophylaxis on the kingside and Rd8, b6-Bb7 next for example. The position is equal.}) (11. b3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gc1b2,Gb3c4] t Protecting the c4 bishop and preparing Bb2.} Bd6 {[%cal Rd6h2] Attacking h2 and developing.} 12. Re1 {Only try for any advantage.} (12. h3 {t} Ne7 {[%csl Be7] Keeping the knight flexible.} 13. Bb2 O-O $11 {[%cal Ge7g6] Ng6 next and an equal game.}) (12. Qh5 {t Defending h2 and bringing the queen to the attack.} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6h5] Developing the knight with tempo.} 13. Qh4 {Only move to not be worse.} b5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Rb5c4] Preparing Bb7 with tempo.} 14. Bd3 Bb7 15. a4 {[%cal Ra4b5] Attacking b5.} b4 $132 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Ge8c8,Ch8g8,Cg7g5] Only move to keep the material balance. 0-0-0 with a sharp game where both sides have equal chances.}) 12... Ne7 $1 {[%csl Be7] Only move to be solid.} 13. Qh5 {[%cal Rc4e6] Bringing the queen to the attack and threatening Bxe6.} Qc5 $11 {[%cal Rc5h5] s To challenge the queen on h5. With an equal position. For example:} 14. Qxc5 Bxc5 15. Bb2 O-O 16. Red1 b6 $11 {[%cal Ge7g6,Gc8b7,Gf8d8] White has some activity but Black is solid.}) (11. Bd3 {[%csl Bd3][%cal Rd3h7] t} Bd6 {[%cal Rd6h2] Developing with an attack.} 12. h3 (12. Re1 {t This move order gives White an extra option.} Nf6 {[%csl Bf6] Preparing 0-0 and stopping Qh5.} 13. g3 $5 {To stop the bishop trade.} (13. h3 {Transposes to 12.h3.}) (13. Nf5 $2 {t Has also been played but loses a pawn.} Bxh2+ 14. Kh1 Kf8 $1 {[%csl Bf8][%cal Re6f5,Gf8g7] Key move that refutes White idea.} 15. g3 {Only move to not lose.} exf5 16. Kxh2 h5 $17 {[%cal Gh5h4] With an extra pawn for Black.}) 13... O-O 14. Bg5 {[%cal Rg5f6] Now White managed to play Bg5.} Be5 {[%cal Ge5f6,Re5d4] Protecting f6 and attacking d4 at the same time.} 15. c3 {White's only logical move.} h6 {[%cal Rh6g5]} 16. Nf3 {[%cal Rf3e5] Only critical move.} Bxc3 {s} 17. Rc1 {[%cal Rc1c7]} ({Or:} 17. Bf4 e5 $1 {Only move to not lose a piece.} 18. Bxe5 {Only move for White to keep the balance.} Bxe5 19. Nxe5 Be6 $11 {With complete equality.}) 17... hxg5 18. Rxc3 Qd8 19. Nxg5 Bd7 $11 {[%csl Bd7][%cal Gd7c6] Finishing development. The position is equal.}) (12. Qh5 {[%cal Gh5h2] t} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6h5] Developing with tempo.} 13. Qh4 Bd7 $1 {[%csl Bd7][%cal Ge8c8] Now we prefer to castle long.} 14. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gb4b5] To meet 0-0-0 with b4-b5.} (14. Bg5 {[%cal Rg5f6] t Attacking the knight on f6. But now we can castle safely:} O-O-O $132 {[%cal Gd6e5,Gh7h6] Be5-h6 next with equal chances.}) (14. c4 $5 {Also an interesting approach.} h5 $1 $132 {[%cal Gf6g4] But here we play the same idea like in 14.Rb1:}) 14... h5 $1 $132 {[%cal Gf6g4] With the idea Ng4. Engine gives 0.00 here but both sides have chances. To demonstrate the idea behind h5:} 15. Rd1 ({So it makes sense for White to avoid the immediate Ng4.} 15. h3 O-O-O $132 {[%csl Gd8,Gh8][%cal Gf6g4] Now where the rooks are connected the idea is availabe again.}) 15... Ng4 {[%cal Rg4h2,Rd6h2]} 16. h3 Be7 $1 {[%cal Re7h4] s} 17. Bg5 {Only move to keep equality.} Bxg5 18. Qxg5 Qe5 $1 $11 {[%cal Re5g5,Re5d4] Only move for Black and the game gets simple now.}) 12... Nf6 {[%csl Bf6][%cal Gf6h5,Rd1h5] Now the knight is preferable on f6 to stop Qh5.} 13. Re1 {[%cal Rd4f5] Most common move threatening Nf5.} (13. c3 {t Is also possible but slow.} h6 {[%cal Rh6g5] Stopping Bg5.} 14. Qf3 {[%cal Rc1h6,Rf3f6] To delay Black's castle.} Be5 {[%cal Ge5f6,Ge8g8] Protecting f6 to prepare 0-0. With an equal position.}) 13... Bh2+ {To make White move his king.} 14. Kh1 Bf4 $1 {[%csl Bf4][%cal Gf4c1] s Eliminating the dark squared bishop, so we don't have to worry about Bg5.} 15. Qf3 {[%cal Rf3f4] Most commonly played.} (15. Bxf4 {Is also possible.} Qxf4 $11 {With also an equal position. For example:} 16. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3e5] Heading to e5.} O-O 17. Kg1 {[%cal Gg1f2] Protecting f2.} b6 $11 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ga8d8]}) 15... Bxc1 16. Raxc1 O-O $11 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gc8d7] Now White has no attack our king and the position is equal.}) (11. Qe2 {[%cal Ge2c4] t Defending the bishop and protecting the bishop.} Bd6 {[%cal Rd6h2] Developing the bishop and attacking h2.} 12. h3 (12. Nf5 $5 {[%csl Bf5][%cal Rf5d6,Rf5g7] t Is an interesting option for White.} Bxh2+ {Now we have to take on h2.} 13. Kh1 Be5 (13... Qe5 14. Nxg7+ Qxg7 15. Kxh2 Ne7 16. Rd1 Bd7 17. Rd3 $14 {1-0 Albornoz Cabrera,C (2579) -Shirov,A (2666) Olympiad-45 Budapest 2024 (3.12)}) 14. Re1 {[%cal Re2e5]} g6 {[%csl Bg6] Only move to keep the balance.} 15. Qxe5 ({Or:} 15. Nh6 {To keep the queens on.} Bd6 $132 {With equal chances. White has a lead in development but Black is solid with an extra pawn.}) 15... Qxe5 16. Rxe5 gxf5 $132 {With chances for both sides. Black has a pawn and is solid but White has the bishop pair and activity}) (12. Re1 {t} Ne7 $11 {[%csl Be7] Also here we prefer to develop instead of taking pawns. The game could follow:} 13. Nf3 O-O 14. Bd3 Bd7 $11 {With a equal position.}) 12... Ne7 {[%csl Be7] To omit Nf5.} 13. c3 {Most common move.} (13. a4 {[%cal Ra4b5] t To stop b5.} O-O 14. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] Preparing Bb2.} Bd7 {Finishing development.} 15. Bb2 Ng6 $11 {[%cal Ga8d8] Rd8 next for example and an equal position.}) 13... O-O 14. Re1 {Most played in this position.} (14. Rd1 {t Has also been played and is similiar.} Ng6 $11) 14... Ng6 $11 {Black has a solid position. For example:} 15. Bb3 b6 $11 {[%cal Gc8b7] Bb7 next and a equal game.}) 11... Bd6 {[%cal Rd6h2] Developing and attacking h2.} 12. h3 (12. Re1 $5 {[%csl Rh2] t Ignoring the hanging pawn in order to quickly orchestrate an attack.} Ne7 {[%csl Be7] It is more sensible to develop than to grab pawns.} 13. Qh5 {Bringing the queen to the attack.} O-O 14. c3 {[%cal Gb3c2] Preparing Bc2.} Ng6 {[%cal Gg6f4] Activating the knight.} 15. Bc2 {[%cal Rc2h7]} b5 16. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3g5] To go to g5.} (16. Re4 {[%cal Re4h4] t With the threat Rh4.} Be7 {Stopping Rh4.} 17. Re3 {[%cal Re3h3] Renewing the threat to bring the rook to the h file.} Qc5 $1 $11 {[%cal Rc5h5] Only move to defend. Black defends and is solid.}) 16... h6 {[%cal Rh6g5] To stop Ng5 entirely.} 17. Re4 {[%cal Ge4g4] Bringing another piece to the attack.} (17. Bxg6 {t Takes a pawn but Black has enough compensation:} fxg6 18. Qxg6 e5 $44 {[%csl Gc8,Gd6][%cal Gc8f5] Black is very active and has the bishop pair.}) 17... Qc5 $11 {[%cal Rc5h5] Attacking the queen to defend conveniently. Black is solid.}) (12. Qh5 {[%cal Gh5h2] t Defending the pawn and activating the queen.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6h5] Now where the queen is on h5 we prefer Nf6.} 13. Qh4 Bd7 {[%cal Ge8c8] Now when the knight is on f6 our king is safer on the queenside.} 14. Bg5 {[%cal Rg5f6]} O-O-O 15. Rad1 {Most common and most logical move.} h6 {[%cal Rh6g5] s Getting the bishop pair.} 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Rd3 {[%cal Rd3c3]} Kb8 {Only move as Rc3 was threatened.} 18. Rc3 {Most direct try.} (18. Rfd1 {Is less critical.} Be7 $132 {[%csl Gd7,Ge7][%cal Ge7f6] Protecting f6. White has the activity now but black has the bishop pair and a solid position.}) 18... Qa5 19. Qxf6 {White has to take on f6 otherwise the position is just worse.} Be5 {[%cal Re5f6,Re5d4]} 20. Qh4 Bc7 $44 {[%csl Gc7,Gd7][%cal Gf7f5,Ge6e5] Black has enough compensation for the pawn and can continue with pushing the pawns.}) 12... Ne7 {[%csl Be7] The knight is more flexible here than on f6.} 13. c3 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gb3c2] Vacating c2 for the bishop.} (13. Re1 {t Is similiar to 13.c3 with 14.Re1.} O-O 14. Qh5 (14. c3 {Transposes to 13.c3.}) 14... Ng6 {[%cal Gg6f4]} 15. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3g5]} Nf4 $11 {With a solid position for Black.}) (13. Be3 {t Normal development move but doesn't impose any problems for Black.} O-O 14. Qe2 {[%cal Ga1d1]} Bh2+ {Forcing the king to h1 before improving the bishop.} 15. Kh1 Be5 $11 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] With a solid position for Black.}) 13... O-O 14. Re1 {Deploying the rook on the semi open file.} (14. Bc2 {t} e5 {[%csl Be5][%cal Re5d4]} 15. Nf3 h6 $11 {[%cal Rh6g5] Controling g5. Black has no problems.}) (14. Qh5 {t With similiar play to 14.Re1.} b5 {[%cal Gc8b7] To prepare Bb7.} 15. Bc2 {[%cal Rc2h7]} Ng6 {Only now when forced the knight moves to g6.} 16. a4 {[%cal Ra4b5]} (16. Re1 {Transposes to 14.Re1.}) 16... b4 $11 {[%cal Rb4c3]} 17. cxb4 Bxb4 $11 {With a solid position for Black.}) (14. Qf3 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Rf3a8] t Developing the queen and stopping b5 (6) .} e5 {[%cal Re5d4] Kicking the knight from d4.} 15. Nc2 a5 {[%cal Ra5a4]} 16. Ne3 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Ge3d5]} Kh8 $11 {[%cal Gf7f5] With an equal position. f5 now is possible for Black.}) 14... b5 {[%cal Gc8b7] To prepare Bb7 and finish development.} 15. Bg5 {[%cal Rg5e7] Activating the bishop.} (15. Qh5 {t} Ng6 16. Bc2 {[%cal Rc2h7] Pinning the knight.} (16. Nf3 {[%cal Rf3g5] Immediately trying to orchestrate an attack on h7. Allows:} Nf4 $11 {[%csl Bf4][%cal Gf4h5]}) 16... Bb7 17. Nf3 h6 $1 $11 {[%cal Rh6g5,Gg6f4] Stopping Ng5 and ready to play Nf4 next.}) (15. a4 $5 $146 {[%cal Ra4b5] t Is also very natural but hasn't been played so far.} b4 $11 {[%csl Gb4] Avoiding all kind of axb5 for White.}) 15... h6 $5 $146 {All 4 games that reached this position saw Ng6 instead.} 16. Bxe7 {Concrete try.} (16. Be3 {t Allows Black to easily equalize.} e5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Re5d4] Taking the center and chasing the knight away.} 17. Nf3 Nf5 $11 {[%cal Rf5e3,Gc8b7] With an equal position.}) 16... Bxe7 17. Qd3 {[%cal Gb3c2,Ga1d1] Only try for activity.} Kh8 $1 {[%cal Gc8b7] Good prophylactical move to enable Bb7.} (17... Bb7 $2 {Loses to:} 18. Nxe6 $1 $18) 18. a4 {[%cal Ra4b5] Most natural move for White.} (18. Bc2 {[%cal Rd3h7] The mate threat is easily blocked.} g6 $11 {And Black has no problems.}) 18... bxa4 {To avoid axb5 and keep the material balance.} 19. Bc2 {[%cal Rd3h7] Forcing g6 before recapturing.} ({Or:} 19. Rxa4 Rb8 $132 {With a similiar position.}) 19... g6 20. Rxa4 {White activates the rook and recaptures the pawn.} Rb8 $132 {[%csl Gc8,Ge7] White is more active but Black has the bishop pair and is solid.} *

