1. e4 {t} e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 (4. Qg4 $2 {t} Nc6 5. Nf3 cxd4 6. Bd3 (6. Nxd4 Nxe5 $17) 6... h5 $1 {[%csl Bh5] First move you need to remember.} 7. Qf4 {Critical, to target the f7 pawn.} (7. Qg3 {t} h4 8. Qg4 Nh6 9. Bxh6 Rxh6 10. O-O f6 $1 $19 {[%csl Bf6] The most precise, Black is just winning.} (10... Bd7 $17 {[%cal Gd8c7,Ge8c8] also good enough.})) 7... f6 $1 {[%csl Bf6] Strong move, Black has a huge advantage.} (7... Bd7 8. O-O Qc7 $13 {[%csl Gf4,Cf7,Gg3][%cal Ge8c8,Gf4f7] Not so clear, compared to 7.Qg3, because the queen is more active.}) 8. Bg6+ Kd7 $17 {[%csl Gd5,Gd7,Ge6][%cal Gf6e5,Gc6e5,Gg8f6,Gf8d6] -1.50 evaluation.}) (4. Nf3 {t} Nc6 {More practical, because yes, we allow White to transpose to the main Advance French, but anyways we need to know it, so we are not scared of it.} (4... cxd4 {is more precise according to the engine, but you need to study one extra line.} 5. Nxd4 $5 {Extra line, you need to learn.} (5. Bd3 Nc6 {transposes to 4...Nc6.})) 5. Bd3 {Logical move, if White chooses the 4.Nf3 move order.} (5. c3 {The best, transposing to the main position.}) 5... cxd4 6. O-O {[%csl Cd4,Ge5][%cal Gf1e1,Gc1f4,Gb1d2,Gd2b3,Gb3d4] White plays for development.} f6 $5 {The most practical move.} 7. Bb5 $1 {The best move, to regain material.} (7. Bf4 $2 {t Huge mistake.} g5 $1 {[%csl Bg5] Typical.} 8. Bg3 f5 $17 {-1 already.}) (7. Qe2 $6 {t also bad.} Bc5 $1 {Just develop and overprotect d4.} (7... fxe5 {The main line, but White can somehow play it.} 8. Nxe5 $44) 8. Nbd2 Nge7 9. Nb3 Bb6 $15 {New position, Black is slightly better.}) 7... Bd7 8. Bxc6 {[%csl Ge5] Logical.} bxc6 $1 {[%csl Gc6,Gd5,Gd7,Oe6][%cal Gc6c5,Gd7e6] Correct recapture for the Advance french, Black plays for a big solid center.} 9. Qxd4 Qb6 {[%csl Gb6] Very straightforward solution.} 10. Qg4 {To stop Black's bishop from developing.} (10. Qf4 {t} Qc7 $5 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge7g6] s Target the pawn and follow the queen.} 11. Re1 Ne7 12. Qd4 Ng6 {Interesting, Black has huge compensation, after:} (12... Nf5 $5 {good enough.}) 13. exf6 gxf6 14. Qxf6 Be7 15. Qc3 Rg8 $36 {[%cal Ge6e5,Ge5e4] Typical french play with initiative.}) 10... Ne7 $146 11. exf6 gxf6 {s} 12. Qh5+ {Critical line:} Ng6 13. Nh4 Rg8 14. Qxh7 Rg7 15. Qh5 O-O-O $3 {Key move.} 16. Nxg6 Be8 $1 {[%csl Be8] The point.} 17. Qh3 Rxg6 18. Qxe6+ Bd7 19. Qf7 Rg4 20. h3 $1 Rg7 21. Qxf6 Rg8 {[%cal Gf8c5] 2 pawns down, but very big initiative:} 22. Be3 Qb7 $36 {White can lose this position in a few moves.} 23. Kh1 $4 {Logical, but already losing!} Bxh3 $3 24. gxh3 Qd7 25. Qf3 Rh8 26. Kg2 Be7 $19 {[%cal Gd8g8] White can resign.}) 4... Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 $5 {[%csl Bd7] Alexey's recommendation.} (5... Qb6 {This was Baadur Jobava's recommendation.}) 6. dxc5 (6. Bd3 {The "French Gambit" will be analyzed in Chapter 5.}) (6. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] is White's second most important move. The idea is b2-b4. We will analyze it in Chapter 6.}) (6. Be2 {The mainline will be extensively analyzed in Chapters 7 and 8.}) (6. g3 {t Very rare move. I mention it only because it has been tried by Niemann (twice) and Bernadskiy.} Qa5 $5 {[%csl Ba5,Rc3][%cal Gc5d4] I like this move. Qa5 pins c3 and prepares cxd4.} (6... Nge7 {[%cal Ge7f5] at is also fine, of course.} 7. Bh3 {[%cal Re7f5,Ch3f5] Bh3 discourages Nf5, but Black can continue with} (7. Bg2 Nf5 $132) 7... Ng6 8. O-O h5 $1 $13 {[%cal Gh5h4] h4 next, with an interesting game.}) 7. dxc5 {critical move.} (7. Bg2 $6 Nxd4 8. Nxd4 cxd4 9. Qxd4 Qc7 $15 {[%csl Re5,Rg2][%cal Gf8c5,Gg8e7] Bc5-Ne7 next, and Black is even preferable.}) 7... Qc7 $1 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf8c5] attacking e5. Black's next move will be Nxe5 or Bxc5.} 8. Bf4 (8. Bg2 Bxc5 9. O-O Nxe5 $13) 8... Bxc5 9. Bd3 Nge7 10. b4 Bb6 11. a4 a6 12. O-O {This happened in the game Bernadsky- Schekachikhin, 2024, and now the engine already prefers Black after} Ng6 13. Bxg6 fxg6 $1 $15 {[%csl Bg6][%cal Ge8g8] 0-0 next, and good play on the 'f' file.}) (6. Be3 {t} Qb6 {The simplest way.} (6... Nge7 $5 {[%csl Re3][%cal Ge7f5] at also possible, with the idea Nf5.} 7. Bd3 {[%cal Re7f5]} Qb6 8. Qd2 c4 {[%csl Bc4][%cal Rd3c2,Gb6b2] s concrete idea: White cannot play Bc2 because of the b2 pawn.} 9. Be2 Nf5 {Interesting position, for example:} 10. Bf4 (10. O-O Nxe3 11. fxe3 Be7 $36 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf7f6] 00-f6 next. Black's position is already more pleasant.}) 10... f6 $1 $146 11. exf6 gxf6 12. O-O O-O-O 13. b3 $1 {[%csl Bb3] only move, otherwise White is seriously worse} Rg8 $5 {engine's move.} (13... Na5 $13 {human move.}) 14. bxc4 dxc4 15. Bxc4 Rg4 $13 {[%cal Ge6e5] e5 next with a very unclear but objectively equal "0.00" position.}) 7. Qd2 cxd4 8. cxd4 Rc8 {[%cal Gc6a5,Ga5c4] with the idea Na5-Nc4.} 9. Nc3 Na5 10. Rc1 (10. Bd3 Nc4 11. Bxc4 Rxc4 12. O-O Ne7 $132 {[%cal Ge7f5] Nf5 next and Black doesn't have any problem.}) 10... Bb4 {we play useful moves and wait for Bd3 before playing Nc4.} 11. Bd3 Nc4 12. Bxc4 Rxc4 13. O-O Bb5 $1 14. Rfe1 Qc6 $15 {[%cal Gb4c3] Bxc3 next.}) (6. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c2] t White's idea is to maneuver the knight to c2, from where it will defend d4. However, this approach is too slow.} cxd4 {the simplest.} (6... f6 $5 {[%csl Bf6] is another good move for a complicated game.}) 7. cxd4 Bb4+ {very safe way.} (7... Bxa3 {is Black's most common continuation. It is also fine, objectively, but I don't want to enter in lines like} 8. bxa3 Qa5+ 9. Bd2 Qxa3 $132 {White has full compensation for the pawn, so the position is equal.}) 8. Bd2 Qa5 {forcing an edngame after} 9. Nc2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 11. Kxd2 f6 12. Bd3 Nge7 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf8f7,Ga8f8] Equal endgame. Very often Black can continue with 0-0, and then Rf7-Raf8 and prepare fxe5, where he will have a great counterplay on the 'f' file.}) 6... Bxc5 7. b4 {Less common than 7.Bd3, but a more testing way.} (7. Bd3 {t White's most common continuation, but it's very risky because Black can play the concrete} f6 $1 8. b4 {White's best idea.} (8. exf6 $2 {t Just bad because after} Nxf6 $17 {[%cal Ge8g8] 00 next, and Black has easy development, good center and great squares for the pieces.}) (8. Qe2 $6 {t} fxe5 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. Qxe5 Nf6 $15 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ge8g8] Qe5 is misplaced.}) (8. Bf4 $6 {t} g5 $1 9. Bg3 (9. Nxg5 $2 {the sacrifice doesn't work.} fxg5 10. Qh5+ Kf8 11. Bxg5 Be7 $19) 9... g4 $17 {Still complicated, but the evaluation is -1,00. No need to analyze it further.}) 8... Bb6 9. b5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 fxe5 11. Qh5+ Kf8 12. Qxe5 Nf6 {[%csl Rf8] s} 13. O-O (13. Ba3+ $6 Kf7 $15 {[%csl Bf7] only helps Black.}) 13... Bc7 14. Qe2 e5 $1 $36 {[%cal Ge5e4,Gd7g4] With the idea e4-Bg4. Here I have found a courious idea:} 15. f3 {[%cal Re5e4,Gc3c4] normal move against e4, White is also ready for c4.} h5 $1 {with the idea:} 16. c4 h4 17. Nc3 $2 {Most natural move, but now Black is winning with} (17. Ba3+ $142 {is the best, and the position is unclear after} Kf7 18. Nc3 Bb6+ 19. c5 Qe7 20. Na4 Ba5 $36 {Unclear, but still some initiative for Black.}) 17... Bb6+ 18. Kh1 Nh5 $19 {[%csl Rh1][%cal Gh5g3]}) 7... Bb6 $1 {[%cal Gg8e7] The right square for the bishop. e7 has to be kept free for the development of the knight.} (7... Be7 8. b5 Na5 9. Bd3 $14 {[%csl Rg8] Problems in developing Ng8.}) 8. b5 {White deviates the knight from c6, where it puts pressure against e5.} (8. Bd3 f6 {trans in 7.Bd3.}) 8... Na5 {Black's most common way, it's also very interesting.} (8... Nce7 $5 {at The safest way.} 9. Bd3 Ng6 {[%cal Gg8e7,Gg8h6] the other knight will go to e7 or h6, according to the situation.} 10. O-O Qc7 {s} 11. Qe2 (11. Re1 Nh6 $5 12. Bxh6 gxh6 13. Qd2 O-O-O $132 {[%cal Gh8g8,Gc8b8] interesting position.}) 11... N8e7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf7f6] Black will continue with 00 and f6 next.} 12. g3 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] standard idea when Black's knight is on g6.} f6 13. exf6 gxf6 14. c4 e5 15. cxd5 Nxd5 16. Be4 Be6 $132) 9. Bd3 Ne7 10. O-O Qc7 {[%cal Ga5c4,Ga8c8] Black will have future counterplay on the 'c' file, while White's hopes are on the kingside.} 11. a4 Ng6 12. Re1 O-O 13. Ba3 Rfc8 {[%cal Ga5c4]} 14. Ng5 {[%cal Gd1h5] The reason why I consider 8...Nce7 safer is that in the 8...Na5 line, sometimes we should be able to find defensive moves like} Qd8 $1 {[%csl Bd8] only move.} 15. Qh5 (15. Qg4 $6 {t} Rc4 $1 {[%csl Bc4] Black's key idea.} 16. Qg3 (16. Bxc4 $2 Nxc4 $17 {This is not compensation, but big positional advantage for Black.}) 16... Rf4 $36 {[%csl Rf2]}) 15... h6 $1 {[%csl Bh6] another only move, and everything will end in a draw after} 16. Nxf7 Nf4 $1 {[%csl Bf4]} 17. Nxh6+ (17. Qf3 $2 Qh4 $17) 17... gxh6 18. Qxh6 Nxd3 19. Qg6+ Kh8 20. Qh6+ Kg8 $11 *

