1. e4 {t} e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 ({In the 5...Qb6 line, the French Gambit is more interesting to play for White} 5... Qb6 6. Bd3 cxd4 7. O-O $5 {[%csl Bg1] is a very serious continuation.}) 6. Bd3 {[%csl Gd3,Rd4] White's bishop is ideally developed on d3. The only problem is that it leaves the d4 pawn vulnerable.} cxd4 7. cxd4 (7. O-O {[%csl Bd7] t this line is more interesting for White against 5...Qb6 than 5...Bd7, because after} dxc3 8. Nxc3 Nge7 {[%csl Cd7] Bd7 is much more useful than Qb6. For example, there is no Be3 with tempo here.} (8... a6 $5 {also good, and this move wouldn't be possible in the 5...Qb6 line, because White would have continued with Be3 + Na4, with a quick counterplay on the b6 square.} 9. Be3 {The position is unclear with chances for three results, for example:} (9. Bg5 $2 Be7 10. Be3 {Kilic-Sonis, 2025.} g5 $17 (10... f6 $17)) 9... Be7 10. Bc2 $5 (10. Na4 $2 d4 $1 11. Nxd4 Nxe5 $17) 10... g5 $13) 9. Bg5 (9. Re1 Ng6 {[%cal Gf8c5,Ge8g8,Gf7f6] we are just ready for the typical Bc5-00-f6.} 10. g3 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] g3-h4 is a typical idea against Ng6.} Bc5 11. h4 h6 {[%cal Ch4h5,Rh5h6] allowing h5, but stopping h6.} 12. h5 Nge7 13. a3 a6 $15 {Complicated position, but objectively Black is preferable.}) 9... a6 {[%csl Ga6][%cal Rc3b5] against Nb5.} 10. Re1 (10. h4 $5 {against Black's future Ng6, ideas, but now I like} h6 11. Be3 g6 $5 $132 {[%cal Gf8g7] Bg7 next.}) 10... h6 11. Be3 (11. Bh4 Qb6 $17 {[%cal Gg7g5,Gf8g7] g5-Bg7 next.}) 11... Ng6 $1 {s no need to be afrai about Bxg6.} 12. Bxg6 fxg6 13. Qd3 Kf7 14. Na4 Be7 15. Bb6 Qe8 16. Nc5 Bc8 17. a3 Rf8 18. Rac1 Kg8 $17 {0-1 Ivanov,M (2359) -Peralta,F (2595) Barcelona Sants op-A 23rd 2022 (4)}) 7... Qb6 {[%csl Bb6,Rd4,Bd7] This position can arise from both 5...Bd7 and 5...Qb6 lines.} 8. O-O (8. Be2 $5 {t This is probably White's most interesting move nowadays.} Nh6 $1 {Much simpler move, the knight gets to f5, but not allowing Na3-Nc2.} (8... Nge7 $6 {is a common mistake.} 9. Na3 $1 {[%csl Rf8] The knight can develop to a3, because the bishop is blocked by the knight.} Nf5 10. Nc2 $132 {Black is fine, but it's a game, it could be a serious line for White.}) 9. Nc3 {This is maximum draw for White.} (9. Bxh6 {t The only extra option.} Qxb2 $1 {Usual intermezzo.} 10. Nbd2 {The only good move.} (10. Bxg7 $2 {In majority of games, White took, but it's just bad.} Bxg7 $19 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Rb1d2,Gc6d4] Positionally and tactically losing for White.}) 10... gxh6 11. O-O $1 $146 {The best move.} (11. Rb1 $2 {is how everybody played in this position, but after} Qxa2 12. Rxb7 Nb4 $1 {Black has a big advantage.} 13. O-O O-O-O $19 {[%csl Rb7] The rook is trapped.}) 11... b6 {[%csl Bb6][%cal Ga1b1,Gb1b7] Useful prophylactic move.} 12. Nb3 $1 Rc8 13. Ne1 $1 {[%cal Gf2f4] is how engine is trying to play it.} a5 $36 {[%cal Ga5a4] With idea a4, White has some kind of compensation, but not full of course, -0.40 for the engine.}) (9. Na3 $6 {t This is not the way now.} Bb4+ $5 {Good intermezzo.} (9... Bxa3 {is also possible of course.} 10. bxa3 Nf5 $15 {[%csl Rd4] Problems with d4 pawn.}) 10. Kf1 O-O $15 {Just slightly better position, similar to the 6.Be2 line.}) 9... Nf5 10. Na4 Qa5+ 11. Nc3 Qb6 $11 {The best, to repeat to moves.} (11... Be7 $5 {You can also play on.} 12. O-O O-O 13. g4 Nh4 {New unclear position.} 14. Nxh4 Bxh4 15. g5 Qd8 16. f4 f6 $13 {if you are ready for an adventure, this is a good way. But personally, I prefer to repeat the moves.})) (8. Bc2 $6 {t Bad way to defend the pawn.} Nb4 $1 9. O-O Nxc2 10. Qxc2 Ne7 $15 {[%cal Ge7f5,Ga8c8] This is slightly better for Black, pair of bishops for free.}) 8... Nxd4 9. Nxd4 $6 {The old mainline is dubious according to modern engines.} (9. Nbd2 {t Modern option.} Nxf3+ {This is extremely safe line.} (9... Bc5 $5 {at This is an ambitious line.} 10. Nxd4 Bxd4 11. Nf3 Ne7 {s} 12. Bd2 $1 {Best move for the engine, really mysterious.} f5 $36 {Black plays for the initiative.}) 10. Nxf3 Bb5 {The only problem is that if White plays well, it will be equal.} 11. Be3 Qa6 12. Bxb5+ Qxb5 13. Nd4 {White has good development, and while Black will try to play Ne7-Nc6, in the meantime White can regain the pawn.} (13. Rc1 {Be careful if White starts with this move:} Qd7 $1 {First, to get the queen to safety and stop Rc7.} (13... Ne7 $2 {is bad.} 14. Rc7 $16 {[%csl Rb5,Gc7,Rf7,Gg5][%cal Gf3d4,Gf3g5,Re7c6] The rook is very active here.}) 14. Nd4 Ne7 {Transposes to 13.Nd4.}) 13... Qd7 14. Rc1 Ne7 {s Transposes to 13.Nd4.} 15. Qd3 {Normal scenario could be:} Nc6 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Rc2 {White wants to double the rooks.} Be7 18. Rfc1 Rc8 19. Qa6 {White regainst the pawn.} c5 $1 {The best way to give it back.} 20. Bxc5 Rxc5 21. Rxc5 Bxc5 22. Rxc5 O-O $11 {Just equal endgame.}) 9... Qxd4 10. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3b5] White has Nb5 ideas.} (10. Qe2 {t has been tried in some games, White's idea is Nd2-Nf3, but it's also quite bad.} a6 11. Nd2 Qa4 $1 $146 {[%csl Ga4,Rd4][%cal Gd7b5] Very precise move, prophylaxis against the knight moves and also prepares Bb5.} (11... Ne7 $6 {This is not precise, White has full compensation after} 12. Nb3 $11 {or 12.Nf3.}) 12. b3 (12. Nb3 Bb5 $17 {Same story.}) (12. Nf3 Bb5 $17 {This is the point.}) 12... Qa5 13. a4 {To stop Bb5, but now just finish development.} (13. Nf3 {is still met with} Bb5 $17) 13... Ne7 $15 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ge7c6] The b4 square is weak.}) 10... a6 $1 {[%csl Ga6][%cal Rc3b5] Important move, to defend the b5 square.} 11. Qe2 (11. Re1 {t was tried in some recent games, but it's also quite bad.} Ne7 12. Be3 {White sacrifices the second pawn.} Qxe5 13. Bc5 Qf6 {Simple move.} (13... Qg5 {is the same, just with one extra move.} 14. Be3 {The best.} Qe5 15. Bc5 Qf6 {see 13...Qf6.}) 14. Qb3 Bc6 $17 {[%cal Ge7g6] No problem and better for Black, of course.}) 11... Ne7 12. Kh1 {[%cal Gf2f4] White's most common idea, to continue with f4.} (12. Be3 {t is bad.} Qxe5 $17) (12. Rd1 {t} Qh4 $17 {Big advantage, -1.}) 12... Nc6 13. f4 Nb4 {Very simple way to play.} 14. Rd1 {White's main try.} (14. Bb1 $6 {t is met with} Qc4 $1 {[%cal Gd5d4] In the endgame, Black has a huge advantage, otherwise d4 is coming.} 15. Qd1 d4 16. Ne4 d3 $19 {Game over, -2 something.}) 14... Bc5 $1 {[%csl Bc5] This is even more precise.} (14... Nxd3 {is a solid option.} 15. Rxd3 Qb6 16. Be3 Bc5 17. Bxc5 Qxc5 $15 {[%cal Rf4f5,Gd7c6] This is slightly better for Black, White has some compensation, but not full.}) 15. Bxa6 Qf2 {[%csl Gf2] This is the point, material is equal now, but Black has a huge positional advantage.} 16. Qxf2 Bxf2 $17 {That's why this line is no longer played nowadays.} *

