1. e4 {t} e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. a3 c4 $5 {[%csl Rb3,Gc4] It's a good way to handle the position. This makes sense, because 6.a3 weakened a lot the b3 square.} 7. Be2 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Ge1g1] Very logical, White wants to finsih development.} (7. Nbd2 {t} f6 $1 {[%csl Rc1,Rd2,Re5,Gf6][%cal Rc1f4] The best plan, to challenge the center. This works well because the knight on d2 blocks the bishop's development.} (7... Na5 $6 {Most common move, but I am not sure that it is the correct plan.} 8. Be2 Bc6 9. Qc2 Qd7 10. Bd1 $14 {[%csl Ga4,Gd1,Rg2][%cal Rg2g3] Compared to the lines with g3, the bishop is better placed on d1.}) 8. Be2 {Most common try, to save a tempo.} (8. exf6 {t} Nxf6 {[%cal Gf8d6,Ge8g8] Black wants to finish development, with a potentially better structure.} 9. Ne5 Bd6 10. f4 O-O 11. Be2 Qb6 $132 {[%cal Re1g1,Gc6e5] For the moment, White can't castle, it's a standard French position.}) (8. g3 {t} Qc7 $5 {To put pressure.} 9. Qe2 fxe5 {[%csl Gc7,Ye2] This inclusion is in our favor.} 10. Nxe5 {The best.} (10. dxe5 $6 {t Rarely a good idea.} Be7 11. Bh3 Nh6 $15 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gh6f7,Ge8c8,Yg7g5,Yh7h5] Black has very simple play.}) 10... Nxe5 11. dxe5 (11. Qxe5 Qxe5+ 12. dxe5 {I see no way for White to be better in the endgame:} Ne7 13. h4 Nc6 14. f4 h5 $5 {[%csl Gh5] Simple decision, Black has no problems.} 15. Nf3 Bc5 $11 {[%cal Ge8e7,Gd5d4]}) 11... Bc5 $132 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge7c6] Playable, equal position.}) 8... fxe5 9. Nxe5 {Necessary.} (9. dxe5 $6 {t Bad move positionally.} Bc5 $15 {[%csl Rd2,Rf3] The knights are stuck.}) 9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Qc7 $1 {[%csl Re5] To immediately attack the e5 pawn.} (10... Ne7 $6 {is a bit slow.} 11. b3 $1 $36 {[%csl Gb3] White could organize something.}) 11. O-O $1 {The best way to sacrifice the pawn.} (11. b3 $6 {t} cxb3 12. Qxb3 Qxe5 $15 {Black is up a pawn.}) 11... Qxe5 12. Re1 Nf6 $5 {No need to hold on to it.} 13. Bxc4 Qc7 $11 {[%cal Ge8c8,Ge8g8,Gf8e7,Gf8d6] You can castle long or short.}) (7. g3 {t Possible setup, second most common.} Na5 $1 {[%csl Ba5][%cal Rf1g2] This time, this plan works better, because the bishop from f1 will go away from the queenside.} 8. Nbd2 Ne7 {We can check one game of GM Caruana:} 9. h4 h6 10. Bh3 Qc7 $5 {[%cal Ge8c8] The easiest plan, to get the king to safety.} (10... Nc8 {[%cal Gc8b6] Black went for this maneuver, but it's not necessary.} 11. O-O Nb6 12. Ne1 $36 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gf2f4] Not clear why we need the knight on b6.}) 11. O-O O-O-O 12. Ne1 {can be met with:} g5 $5 {[%csl Gc8,Ge7,Rg1,Gg5] s Typical reaction, Black is safe enough.} (12... f5 $5 {[%cal Gg7g5] also a standard way.} 13. exf6 {Necessary.} gxf6 $13 {[%cal Ge6e5,Ge1g2] 3 results position.}) 13. Ng2 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Gg2h4] White defends.} gxh4 14. Nxh4 Ng6 $1 $13 {Position is complicated and double-edged.}) (7. b3 $6 {t Premature.} cxb3 8. Qxb3 f6 $1 {[%csl Bf6] Standard plan.} (8... Na5 $6 {Common mistake.} 9. Qc2 Ne7 10. a4 $1 $14 {[%cal Gc1a3,Gf1d3] White could be better here.}) 9. Bd3 (9. exf6 {t} Nxf6 $11 {[%cal Rb3b7] We are not scared of Qxb7.}) (9. Qxb7 $2 {t Very bad.} Rb8 10. Qa6 fxe5 11. dxe5 Bc5 $17 {[%csl Gb8,Gc5,Gc6] Black has fantastic development.}) 9... fxe5 10. dxe5 Qc7 11. O-O Bc5 $11 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gg8e7,Ge8g8] The queen is not so great on b3.}) (7. Bf4 {t} Qb6 8. Qc2 f6 $1 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gd7e8,Ge8g6] Don't forget about the future tempo on the queen.} 9. exf6 (9. Be2 $6 {t is met with:} g5 $1 {[%csl Bg5][%cal Gg5g4] Typical idea and Black is seriously better.} 10. Bg3 g4 11. Nh4 fxe5 12. dxe5 Nh6 $17 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Ge8c8,Gf8e7] The pieces are good, and White is stuck.}) 9... gxf6 $5 {[%csl Gf6] Good moment to take with the pawn.} 10. Be2 Nge7 $36 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Ge7g6] Black will use the bishop on f4 for tempi.}) (7. Be3 {t} Qb6 8. Qc2 f6 $5 {[%csl Gf6] Standard plan.} 9. Nbd2 Qc7 10. exf6 Nxf6 $11 {[%cal Gf8d6] Black has nothing to worry about.}) (7. h4 $6 {t looks active, but it's just a concession.} f6 $1 $15 {[%csl Rg4][%cal Gg8f6] The g4 square is weak.}) 7... f6 $5 {[%csl Re2,Rh5][%cal Rd1h5] Because of the bishop on e2, this plan makes sense, since White can't use the h5 square for the queen.} 8. exf6 {The critical try, to use the fact that White's knight is still on b1.} (8. O-O {t} fxe5 9. Nxe5 {[%cal Gf2f4] The most logical, White wants to set up a blockade.} Nxe5 10. dxe5 Qc7 $1 {[%csl Re5] Black has to act fast.} 11. Be3 $5 $146 {Tricky idea.} (11. f4 $6 {t too slow.} Bc5+ $1 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge7f5] Black develops a fast initiative.} 12. Kh1 Ne7 13. Nd2 Nf5 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gf5d4] The knight does a great job on this square.} 14. Nf3 O-O-O $15 {Slightly better.}) (11. Nd2 Qxe5 {We transpose to 7.Nbd2.}) (11. Bf4 {t Not scary.} Bc5 12. Nd2 Ne7 13. Bh5+ $1 {The best.} (13. Nf3 $6 O-O $15 {[%cal Ge7g6] Black is slightly better.}) 13... g6 {s} 14. Bg4 O-O 15. Bh6 $5 {[%csl Gg5,Gh6][%cal Gd2f3,Gf3g5,Rf8f7] White is threatening to get a positional bind, that's why:} Nc6 $3 {[%csl Bc6] Black can give up the exchange.} 16. Bxf8 Rxf8 {Full compensation, for example:} 17. Nf3 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Qxe5 19. Qd2 h5 20. Bh3 Qf4 $1 {[%csl Bf4] The endgame is better for Black:} 21. Qxf4 Rxf4 $15 {[%csl Gc5,Rf1,Rf2,Gf4][%cal Ra1e1,Gg8f7,Gg6g5] White is tied down.}) 11... Ne7 $5 {Normal move, if you prefer to avoid complications.} (11... Qxe5 {can be met with:} 12. Bh5+ $1 {[%csl Ge3,Re5][%cal Rg7g6,Ge3d4] The point is that g6 is impossible, because of Bd4.} Kd8 $1 $13 {[%csl Gd8] Position is unclear, White has compensation for equality, but not more.}) 12. Nd2 Nf5 13. Bf4 Be7 {[%cal Rd2f3,Ge8g8] s Black just wants to finish development.} 14. Bh5+ g6 15. Bg4 Rf8 $5 16. Nf3 Nh4 $1 $132 {[%csl Rf3,Rf4,Bh4] Using the vulnerable bishop. If we trade the last pair of knights, Black is doing excellent.}) 8... Nxf6 9. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gf4d6,Rf8d6,Gf3e5] White's idea, to fight against Bd6 and support the e5 square.} Nh5 $5 $146 {[%csl Bh5] The easiest is to go for this concrete option.} (9... Qb6 $5 $146 {also deserves attention.} 10. Qc1 $5 {[%csl Bc1] Tricky, the queen is safer here.} (10. Qc2 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Nbd2 Be8 $1 $36 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Ge8g6] To develop on g6 with tempo.}) 10... Be7 11. Nbd2 O-O 12. O-O Nh5 $1 {[%csl Bh5] We start the counterplay on the f-file.} 13. Be5 Rf5 {transposes to 10.Be5.}) 10. Be5 {More logical, to have a strong piece on e5, but in a typical fashion, Black can play agianst it:} (10. Bg5 {t} Be7 {We can change the bishops, no need to be afraid.} 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. g3 {White stops Nf4.} (12. O-O {White will sooner or later need g3.} O-O 13. Re1 $6 {runs into:} Qf6 $1 $15 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Ge6e5,Rb1d2] Black is slightly better, because problems with the f2 pawn.}) 12... O-O 13. O-O Nf6 {[%csl Bf6] s The knight returns.} 14. Nbd2 e5 $5 {Not the only plan, but a straight-forward one.} (14... Be8 $5 {Another idea, to improve the bishop.} 15. Re1 h6 $1 {[%csl Bh6][%cal Gg6h7,Ge8g6,Rf3h4] Important move, to have the h7 square.} 16. Qc2 Rd8 {White doesn't have a clear way to improve the position:} 17. Bf1 Bh5 18. Bh3 Ne4 $1 {[%csl Be4] Tactical ideas in the air.} 19. Nxe4 dxe4 20. Nd2 e5 $1 $13 {Double edged battle, that's why I also recommned the solid 14...e5.}) 15. Nxe5 $5 {[%csl Ge5] Most accurate way to take.} (15. dxe5 Ng4 $5 {extra option.} (15... Nxe5 {transposes to the main.})) 15... Nxe5 16. dxe5 Qxe5 {[%csl Gg2,Rg3][%cal Gg3g2] With a pawn on g2, maybe White could argue for something (very little anyway) , but here, the position is just unclear:} 17. Nf3 Qf5 18. Nd4 Qg6 $132 {[%csl Gd4,Rg2,Rh3][%cal Gd7h3,Gh7h5,Gh5h4] The knight on d4 stays well, but doesn't generate one single threat, while Black can start creating some ideas on the kingside.}) 10... Qb6 $5 {[%csl Rb2] Good tempo.} 11. Qc1 Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. Nbd2 {Now it's an instructive moment:} Rf5 $1 {[%csl Bf5][%cal Ga8f8] Very good way to improve the pieces, we are not afraid of anything.} 14. Rb1 $5 {[%cal Gb2b3] Engine prepares the b3 idea.} (14. g4 $4 {t doesn't work.} Nf4 $1 $19 {[%cal Rf4e2,Ge5f4,Gf5f4] with a winning advantage.}) 14... Nxe5 {We can take on e5.} (14... Raf8 $6 {not great.} 15. b3 $1 $14 {White is better.}) 15. Nxe5 Nf4 $1 {[%csl Re5,Bf5][%cal Gf5e5] And you can already smell the idea of 13...Rf5, Black is going to sacrifice an exchange.} 16. Qd1 (16. Bg4 {t} Rxe5 $1 {Nice idea.} 17. dxe5 Nd3 $36 {[%csl Rc1,Re5][%cal Gd3e5,Gd3c1] With a big initiative.}) 16... Rxe5 $5 {Not necessary, but the most interesting.} 17. dxe5 Bc5 $13 {[%csl Rf2][%cal Ga8f8] Position is unclear, but Black has full compensation.} *

