1. e4 {t} e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Be2 {The theoretical main line.} f6 $5 {[%csl Bf6] I prefer this over 6...Nge7, it's more forced and more interesting.} 7. O-O {The main line by far.} (7. exf6 {t} Nxf6 {[%csl Gf6] White helped us develop.} 8. O-O {The game usually continues with:} (8. Bf4 {t is met with:} Qb6 $1 $36 {[%csl Rb2,Rd4] Difficult to defend both pawns.}) 8... Bd6 (8... cxd4 $5 $11 {[%cal Gf8d6] at}) 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. c4 O-O $11 {Black has finished development, with a lot of good ways to handle the position.}) (7. Bf4 $5 {t Tricky option, quite rare.} cxd4 $5 {The simplest.} (7... Qb6 {at The most logical.} 8. O-O $5 {[%csl Gg1] White doesn't care about the pawn.} g5 $1 $36 {[%csl Gd8,Bg5][%cal Ge8d8] This is the point behind Qb6, Black has the d8 square for the king.} (8... Qxb2 $2 {Taking is too dangerous.} 9. Nbd2 $1 Qxc3 10. Rb1 $16 {[%csl Rc3] The queen is in a very sad situation.}) 9. Nxg5 $2 {doesn't work anymore.} fxg5 $17 {[%csl Gd8][%cal Re2h5,Ge8d8] Black can hide on d8.}) (7... g5 $4 {Don't fall for this trap.} 8. Nxg5 $1 $18 {[%csl Re8][%cal Rf6g5,Ge2h5] Black can resign.}) 8. O-O $1 $146 {The best move.} (8. cxd4 $2 {t} g5 $1 $146 {[%cal Rf3g5,Gf8b4] This move is possible now, because we have Bb4+ and the f8 square for the king.} 9. Be3 g4 $15 {[%csl Rd4,Re5][%cal Gf6e5] Take on e5 next, with a serious advantage.}) 8... dxc3 9. Nxc3 Nge7 {White is playing gambit style, very unclear:} 10. exf6 gxf6 11. Nb5 $1 {[%cal Gb5d6] The best move, White is threatening Nd6#.} (11. Nh4 $2 {is met with:} Ng6 $1 {[%csl Gg6][%cal Ge8f7] The knight is safe on g6, offering the f7 square for the king.} 12. Bh5 Kf7 $15 {[%csl Gf7][%cal Gh8g8,Gc6e7] Black has many defensive ideas, and the extra pawn is long term.}) 11... Ng6 $1 {[%csl Gg6] s} 12. Bc7 $1 {[%csl Gc7] White should jump in with the bishop.} (12. Nc7+ $2 {too optimistic.} Kf7 $17 {[%csl Rc7,Rf4] Black has a close to winning advantage.}) 12... Qc8 13. Bg3 {[%csl Rc8,Gg3][%cal Gb5c7,Ra8c8] Safe move, White is looking for Nc7 now.} Kf7 14. Nc7 (14. Rc1 Qd8 15. Bc7 Qe8 $15 {Position is unclear, but engine prefers Black.}) 14... Rb8 15. Nb5 a6 $1 {[%csl Ba6] This is not an exchange sacrifice, because White can't take it.} (15... Ra8 $11 {Draw by repetition.}) 16. Nd6+ $1 {Necessary.} (16. Bxb8 $2 {too risky.} Qxb8 $17 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Gh8g8] Black is just seriously better.}) 16... Bxd6 17. Bxd6 Ra8 18. Rc1 {White has compensation for the pawn, but also Black is very safe:} Kg7 $5 {[%csl Gg7] Useful move.} 19. b4 Qd8 $44 {[%cal Ga8c8] Rc8 next, I prefer Black.}) (7. Bb5 $5 {t This is a positional sideline, and it was played one month ago in the game: Idani-Sankalp, Bundesliga 2025.} Nxe5 $5 $146 {[%csl Be5][%cal Rd4e5,Gd7b5] This is a brave novelty, and I can see why nobody played it.} (7... fxe5 $6 {is met with:} 8. Bxc6 $1 {[%csl Gc6] White's point.} Bxc6 9. Nxe5 Nf6 10. Qe2 $14 {[%csl Ge5] White has a comfortable position.}) (7... cxd4 $5 $146 {Possible alternative.} 8. cxd4 Bb4+ (8... Nxe5 {will lead to very similar positions as 7...Nxe5.}) 9. Bd2 (9. Nc3 Nxe5 $5 {Maybe we can reach an improved version, for example:} 10. Nxe5 fxe5 11. Qh5+ Kf8 {[%csl Gb4,Bf8] The difference.} 12. Bxd7 Qxd7 13. Qxe5 Nf6 $11 {[%cal Gf8f7] Probably a safer version, just equal.}) 9... Nge7 10. exf6 gxf6 11. Nc3 O-O $132 {A bit more double edged and less forcing, should be interesting to play for both sides.}) 8. Nxe5 {The critical line:} fxe5 9. Qh5+ Ke7 $1 {[%csl Be7] Necessary.} (9... g6 $2 {Positional mistake.} 10. Qxe5 $1 $16 {[%csl Ge5,Rf6,Rg7] The dark squares are too weak.}) 10. Bxd7 Kxd7 $1 {[%csl Gd7] The king is actually safe in the center.} 11. Qxe5 {More logical, to keep the position open.} (11. dxe5 Ne7 {[%cal Gd8e8,Ga8d8,Gd7c8] Black can easily improve it, for example:} 12. c4 Qe8 13. Qf3 Rd8 $132 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gd7c8] Kc8 next and Black is not worse.}) 11... Qc7 $1 {[%csl Bc7] s Good move, to offer a queen trade.} (11... Nf6 $6 {Not the most precise.} 12. Bf4 $36 {[%csl Ge5,Gf4][%cal Gf4c7] White controls the diagonal.}) 12. Qe2 cxd4 13. O-O Bd6 14. g3 {Position is double-edged, but equal, for example:} Re8 $1 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Gg8e7,Ge8e6] To prepare Ne7, and control the e6 square.} (14... Ne7 $6 {Premature.} 15. Re1 $14 {[%csl Re6] Concrete problem.}) 15. cxd4 Ne7 {Overall, Black's pieces are very well placed.} 16. Nc3 Qc4 $1 $36 {[%csl Gc4] Black can easily overtake the initiative.}) 7... fxe5 {[%cal Gd4e5,Gf3e5] White has two possible recaptures.} 8. dxe5 {This one is less played, but still very serious.} (8. Nxe5 {The main response, and it will be the topic of the following chapter.}) 8... Nh6 $1 {[%csl Bh6] The best move, we want to just finish kingside development.} (8... Qc7 $6 {[%cal Ge8c8] A lot of games took a natural path, that according to engine is very bad for us:} 9. Re1 $1 O-O-O $6 10. Bf1 $1 $16 {The evaluation is big already, for example:} Nh6 11. Na3 $1 $146 a6 {[%cal Ra3b5] To stop Nb5.} 12. Rb1 $1 {Strong move.} Nf7 13. b4 $1 $18 {[%csl Gb1,Gb4,Rc8] White has a decisive attack.}) 9. c4 {Most common and it's critical.} (9. Bxh6 {t Not scary.} gxh6 $132 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gd8c7,Ge8c8] Bg7 next and then 00 or Qc7 followed by 000.}) (9. Re1 {t Natural try.} Nf7 $1 {[%csl Gf7] Logical.} (9... Be7 $6 {was played in Aditya-Siddharth, Sharjah Masters 2024, but there is no need to rush with this move.} 10. c4 $1 d4 11. Bxh6 $1 $146 {[%csl Re7] The bishop is misplaced.} gxh6 12. Qd2 $14 {[%csl Re7,Rh6] Black has some unpleasant problems.}) 10. c4 d4 $1 {[%csl Gd4] Necessary, otherwise the center collapses.} 11. Nbd2 Be7 12. Ne4 $1 {[%cal Gc1f4] The best, to be ready to meet Qc7 with Bf4.} (12. Bd3 $6 {Natural, but bad.} Qc7 $1 {[%csl Bc7,Re5] To pressure the pawn.} 13. Qe2 O-O-O $15 {[%csl Re5,Rf3][%cal Gg7g5,Gh7h5] Compared to 8...Qc7, there is no attack on the queenside, and Black is fully ready to launch with g5.}) 12... O-O (12... Ncxe5 $2 {Quite risky.} 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Bh5+ $1 $36 {[%csl Gh5][%cal Ge4c5,Rg7g6] Key intermezzo, followed by Nxc5 and I am quite scared to face it with Black.}) 13. Bf4 {We are still following the game Kalezic-Keinanen, 1-0, EU-chT 2023.} Nh8 $5 {[%csl Gh8] Interesting maneuver.} 14. Bg3 Be8 $5 $146 {[%cal Ge8g6] Probably it was better to improve the bishop.} 15. Nd6 Bg6 {[%csl Rb1,Gg6][%cal Rd6b7,Gd8b6] s} 16. Bd3 Qd7 $11 {Balanced position, but the knight on d6 alone can't do much damage.}) 9... d4 $1 {[%csl Bd4] As usual, Black's only response.} 10. b4 $5 {This is White's critical try, played by GM Shirov and GM Bartel.} (10. Re1 Nf7 {transposes to 9.Re1.} (10... Nf5 $5 $36 {is maybe even stronger.})) (10. Bxh6 {t} gxh6 $132 {[%csl Re5][%cal Gf8g7,Gd8c7] This is not scary, we can pressure the e5 pawn.}) (10. Nbd2 {t} Be7 11. Ne4 Nf7 $11 {Black is doing okay.}) (10. Bf4 {t} Be7 $132 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gh6f5] 0-0, followed by Nf5 next.}) 10... cxb4 {The most critical try, and it was played in Shirov-Stocek, 0-1, Prague Challengers 2019.} (10... Nxb4 $2 {GM Skoberne fell for White's trap.} 11. Bxh6 $1 gxh6 12. Nxd4 $1 $18 {[%cal Rc5d4,Ge2h5,Gd1d4] This was White's idea, and slowly he converted the winning advantage. Bartel-Skoberne, 1-0, EU-chT 2023.}) 11. Nbd2 $5 $146 {Engine's try.} (11. Bd3 $6 {t was played in the game, but it's not the most precise.} Be7 $1 $146 {[%csl Be7] Black is preferable according to the engine.}) 11... Be7 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8] We focus on castling, not wasting time on Nf7, since it's not yet decided where the knight belongs.} 12. Ne4 O-O $1 (12... Nf7 $6 {a bit passive.} 13. c5 $1 $40 {[%csl Rd7,Ge4,Re7,Rf7][%cal Gc1b2] Black's pieces are a bit stuck.}) 13. Bxh6 $5 {The most critical.} (13. c5 {t} Nf5 $1 {[%csl Gd4,Gf5][%cal Gf5d4] The knight will protect d4.} 14. g4 {The best, but quite risky.} (14. Nd6 $6 {allows:} b6 $1 $15 {Black is better.}) (14. Bb2 {is met with:} b6 $1 $36 {Good position.}) 14... Nh4 $5 $13 {or ...Nh6, with a double edged battle.}) 13... gxh6 14. c5 b6 $5 {[%csl Gb6] This is more human I believe.} (14... Rf4 $5 {[%csl Bf4][%cal Gf8g7,Gd8f8,Gg8h8] A strange recommendation by engine.} 15. Nd6 {White should jump immediately.} (15. Bd3 $6 {slow.} Qf8 $15 {[%cal Re4d6,Gb7b6] Nd6 is met with b6, and Black is fully mobilized.}) 15... Bxd6 16. cxd6 {is met with:} (16. exd6 Qf6 $13 {[%cal Ga8g8,Gg8h8,Ya8f8] Position is unclear, but quite funny to play.}) 16... Qa5 $1 {[%csl Ba5,Re5][%cal Ga5e5] Important move, to target the e5 pawn.} 17. g3 Rf7 18. Nxd4 {The best and the line continues with:} Qxe5 19. Nb3 a5 $13 {Very sharp battle, but at least Black is a pawn up.}) 15. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2h6] White attacks h6 and here it's important to know:} Qe8 $3 {[%csl Be8][%cal Ge8g6,Rd2h6] Fantastic prophylactic move, we want to meet Qh6 with Qg6.} 16. Qxh6 Qg6 $132 {Without queens, the endgame is balanced. As you see, the lines are very rich, and for 3 results always, that's why, we need to wait for more games, to understand where the theory will develop.} *

