1. e4 {t} e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Bd7 6. Be2 f6 7. O-O fxe5 8. Nxe5 {The main line.} Nxe5 {The most solid.} (8... cxd4 $5 {possible alternative, but Black is running some structural risks.} 9. cxd4 Bd6 {[%csl Gd6] Black's idea is to play for fast development.} 10. Nxc6 $5 {The most critical.} (10. Nxd7 Qxd7 $132 {[%cal Gg8f6,Ge8g8] Nf6-00 next, Black has a good position, the development lead compensates for the pair of bishops.}) (10. Re1 {was played in Grischuk-Jobava, 0-1, Beijing Blitz 2012.} Nxe5 $1 $146 {[%csl Ge5] We can improve over the game.} (10... Nf6 $2 {Natural, but it was a mistake.} 11. Bh5+ $1 $146 {[%csl Gh5] Key improvement over the game.} g6 12. Bf3 {White has a big advantage, because it's not easy for Black to finish development:} O-O $6 13. Bh6 $1 {[%csl Bh6] Good tempo.} Re8 14. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Rd7,Re8,Gh6] Black's pieces are stuck.}) 11. dxe5 Bc5 $132 {[%csl Ye1,Rf2] Due to the rook being on e1 already, somewhere there will be an anoying tempo on f2 and Black is doing well.}) 10... bxc6 $1 {[%csl Yc6,Yd5,Gd6,Gd7,Ye6] Necessary, and I agree that the structure looks funny, but it's playable.} (10... Bxc6 $2 {Mistake, since it allows:} 11. Bg4 $1 $16 {[%csl Re6][%cal Gf1e1] With serious pressure on e6.}) 11. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2f3,Gd2b3] Most logical move, the knight is headed to f3 or b3.} a5 $1 $146 {[%csl Ca5] Computer makes this abstract move, the best waiting move in the position apparently.} (11... Nf6 $6 {was played in the recent game: Oro-Bacrot, 0-1, Djerba Masters 2025.} 12. Bh5+ $1 $146 {[%csl Gh5] I am afraid of engine's improvement.} (12. Nf3 {Oro's choice.} O-O $132 {[%cal Gc6c5,Ge2d3] Black has a playable position.}) 12... g6 13. Be2 {[%csl Ye2,Rg6][%cal Rg6g7] White lost a tempo, but unfortunately, our pawn from g6 can't go backwards.} O-O 14. Nf3 $14 {[%cal Gc1h6,Cd8b8] White is ready for Bh6, it can get very unpleasant, although after engine move 14...Qb8 it is still possible to play it.}) 12. Bh5+ {is not so scary anymore.} g6 13. Be2 Nh6 $1 {[%csl Bh6][%cal Gh6f7] This is the point, our knight will develop to f7, from where it controls all the dark squares in the position.} 14. Nf3 Nf7 $1 $132 {[%csl Cf7][%cal Cf7h6,Cf7g5,Cf7e5] The best square for the knight. But okay, the position is very deep, and it's tough to analyze, that's why this will not be my main recommendation.}) 9. dxe5 Qc7 {[%csl Yc6,Yf3] We have seen this structure in the previous chapter, but here without the f3 and c6 knights, the dynamics change a bit.} 10. Re1 $5 {White's most interesting try.} (10. c4 {t White's most common move.} Qxe5 $5 {[%csl Ge5] The most forcing response.} (10... O-O-O $5 {at also deserves attention.} 11. cxd5 Qxe5 12. Nc3 Nf6 $11 {[%cal Rd5e6,Gd7c6] This was played in the recent game: Paichadze-Sargsyan, 0-1, EU-ch 2025. Black is doing okay.}) (10... d4 $6 {This was an automatic response with the knights included, but here it's a better version for White.} 11. Re1 $14 {[%cal Ge2d3,Yd1h5] Very often the queen can join the battle more easily.}) 11. Bh5+ $1 {[%csl Gh5] Typical intermezzo.} g6 12. Bf3 Bd6 $5 {[%csl Rh2][%cal Ge5h2] We should also develop with tempo.} 13. g3 Ne7 $1 {Visually, it looks a bit scary to enter this line, but for the engine it's okay.} 14. Nc3 (14. Bf4 $2 {is met with:} Qxb2 $17 {[%csl Ra1][%cal Gb2a1] The point.}) 14... O-O {[%cal Rc1f4,Gf8f4] Still stopping Bf4.} 15. Bh6 Rxf3 $1 {[%csl Bf3] We can sacrifice the exchange.} 16. Qxf3 Qf5 $36 {[%cal Gd7c6,Rf3g2] The bishop will be a monster on c6.} 17. Qxf5 $2 {is a mistake.} Nxf5 $1 $17 {[%csl Gd6,Gd7,Gf5,Rg1][%cal Gd7c6,Gf5d4] Black doesn't have compensation, but a serious advantage.}) (10. Bf4 {t was used in a few blitz games by GM Nepo.} Ne7 11. a4 $5 {[%cal Gb1a3,Ga3b5] This is White's idea, quite tricky, especially for blitz games.} (11. Nd2 O-O-O 12. b4 $5 {[%csl Gd2] The only idea of having a knight on d2.} c4 $1 {[%csl Bc4] We change the pawn structure.} 13. Nf3 h6 {[%cal Gg7g5] Black creates counterplay on the kingside.} 14. Nd4 g5 15. Bg3 Bg7 $13 {[%csl Gd4,Re5] The knight is nice, but we can play around it.}) (11. c4 {is met with:} O-O-O $1 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gd7c6] The knight is not on c6 anymore, so Black has more space for pieces.} 12. Nc3 {We can follow the game Grachev-Zhurova, RUS-chT 2024.} dxc4 $1 {[%csl Gc4] Good reaction.} (12... Bc6 $6 {a bit too early.} 13. Bg4 $1 $40 {[%csl Re6] e6 is weak.}) 13. Bxc4 Kb8 $1 {[%csl Gb8] Good prophylaxis.} 14. Qg4 Nf5 15. Bg5 Rc8 {Not a mistake.} (15... Re8 $5 $146 {also interesting.} 16. Rad1 h6 $13) 16. Rad1 h6 17. Bc1 g5 $1 $146 {[%csl Bg5] Computer improvement.} 18. Ne4 Nd4 $132 {Complicated position, objectively balanced.}) 11... Nc6 $1 {[%csl Gc6] Logical move, there is no need to reveal cards.} (11... O-O-O $2 {Abdusattorov fell for it.} 12. Na3 $1 {Nepo was seriously better.} a6 {stops Nb5, but:} 13. Nb5 $3 {[%csl Bb5] It still works! Amazing refutation.} (13. b4 $5 $16 {also good enough for a big advantage.}) 13... axb5 14. axb5 Kb8 15. Qa4 Qb6 16. c4 $16 {[%csl Rb8] The attack is big, and the evaluation is not good for Black.}) 12. Bg3 $1 $146 {Probably the best.} (12. Na3 $6 {t} a6 $15 {[%csl Ra3] Black is slightly better.}) 12... Be7 $132 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ge8g8] Playable position for 3 results.}) (10. f4 {t} Nh6 {Black can also just develop.} 11. Nd2 Be7 12. Nf3 Bc6 {[%csl Gc6] The game is balanced, for example:} 13. Bd3 g6 14. Be3 Nf5 15. Bf2 O-O $11 {[%cal Gc7d7,Gc6b5,Gf5g7] Many possible ideas for Black.}) 10... O-O-O $1 {[%csl Gc8] Without the knights on the board, Black can safely castle long.} (10... Ne7 $6 {is a bit slow.} 11. c4 d4 12. Bd3 $14 {White is better.}) 11. Bf1 {Main move.} (11. a4 {t was played in the game Robson-Caruana, 2025.} Qxe5 $1 {[%csl Ge5] Black can take the pawn.} 12. Na3 Nf6 13. g3 $5 {Interesting preparation, but Caruana was also ready:} Qf5 $1 {s} 14. Nb5 a6 15. Bd3 {And the game finished in a repetition after:} Qh5 16. Be2 Qf5 17. Bd3 $11 {Draw.}) 11... Ne7 {This line is used quite often by GM Erigaisi.} 12. a4 {[%cal Gb1a3,Ga3b5] White prepares Na3-Nb5.} (12. b4 $5 $146 {t We can ignore.} Kb8 $13 {[%cal Rb4c5,Ge7f5] Unclear new position.}) 12... Nf5 $1 {[%csl Bf5] The knight belongs to f5.} (12... Nc6 $2 {[%csl Rc6] Be careful of putting a knight to c6.} 13. Na3 $1 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Ga3b5] The knight goes to b5, and White has some serious threats.} a6 14. Nb5 $3 $16 {[%csl Bb5] Typical refutation.}) 13. Na3 c4 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Rf1] Good reaction, to close the bishop's diagonal.} (13... a6 $6 {is still met with:} 14. Nb5 $3 $40 {[%csl Bb5] With attack.}) 14. b3 {or 14.b4 leads to the same:} (14. Nb5 $2 {t Positional mistake.} Bxb5 15. axb5 Bc5 $1 $40 {[%csl Bc5,Rf2][%cal Gh8f8] It is Black who has a bit attack now. Kesidis-Fromm, 0-1, Skopje op 2024.}) 14... cxb3 15. Qxb3 Bc5 $1 {[%csl Bc5] Position is interesting and playable for both sides, but objectively Black should be okay.} 16. Nb5 Bxb5 17. axb5 Rhf8 {We are following the game Moussard-Erigaisi, 0-1, Biel Rapid 2023.} 18. Qa2 $1 {[%csl Ga2] White played the strongest engine move.} Kb8 {Erigaisi's choice.} (18... Qe7 $5 {at A safer move, to stop Ba3.} 19. c4 Kb8 $132 {Just playable position.}) 19. Ba3 Ne7 $5 $146 {[%csl Be7][%cal Ge7c8] This is the safest move, and Black slowly solved all opening problems. It was a critical line to know, but it is very unbalanced and double edged.} (19... Bb6 $5 $13 {at Interesting exchange sacrifice, that later paid off, but there is no need.}) *

