1. e4 {t} e6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 ({Against} 3. Bd3 {you can still use} c5 $5 {[%csl Bc5] and after} 4. exd5 exd5 {it transposes to the mainline of this chapter.}) 3... exd5 {The French Exchange was never particularly dangerous, but this time we suggest a straight-forward equalizer, with little theory to remember.} 4. Nf3 {The main line.} (4. Bd3 {t} c5 $5 {Simple choice.} 5. Nf3 (5. dxc5 Bxc5 6. Nf3 Nf6 {also transposes to 4.Nf3.}) 5... c4 {[%csl Gc4] Compared to 4.Nf3, White doesn't have the Re1+ possibility.} 6. Be2 Nf6 {s} 7. O-O {transposes to the Nepo-Abasov game.}) (4. Qf3 $6 {t} Nf6 5. h3 c5 $1 $15 {[%csl Rf3] Black is fast.}) 4... Nf6 5. Bd3 (5. Bg5 {t possible move, but Black can immediately chase the bishop:} h6 $5 6. Bh4 g5 $1 {[%csl Bg5] Best reaction.} 7. Bg3 Bg7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Ne4 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Ge4g3] And Black will play with the pair of bishops.} 10. Nc3 Nxg3 11. hxg3 Be6 $11 {[%cal Gb8c6] Black is very comfortable.}) 5... c5 $5 {[%csl Gc5] This is our recommendation, it's a straight-forward equalizer, that was used by GM Abasov at the Candidates Tournament in 2024.} 6. O-O {Main reply.} (6. c3 {t was tried in Gukesh-Ding, World-ch Match 2024.} c4 $5 {[%csl Gc4] Good way.} 7. Bc2 Bd6 8. O-O {Main move, and it's a playable position.} (8. Qe2+ $5 {t Gukesh tried his luck in the endgame.} Qe7 9. Qxe7+ Kxe7 10. O-O Re8 {The endgame should be equal:} 11. Re1+ Kf8 12. Rxe8+ Kxe8 13. Bg5 Nbd7 14. Nbd2 {It's how the game continued:} h6 15. Bh4 Nh5 16. Re1+ Kf8 17. g4 Nf4 18. Bg3 Nb6 $36 {Ding was slightly better at some point as well.}) 8... O-O 9. h3 {was played in Nakamura-Abasov, 1-0, Candidates 2024.} (9. Bg5 $6 {t Common move, but not precise.} Bg4 $1 $36 {[%csl Rc3,Gc4,Gg4] Black is preferable, thanks to the extra space.}) (9. Ne5 $5 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf2f4] t White wants to get a solid knight on e5.} Nc6 10. f4 {[%csl Rc1] However the bishop is out of the game.} Qc7 $1 {[%csl Bc7][%cal Gc6e7,Rf4f5,Gb7b5] Good move, to prepare Ne7 or b5.} 11. Nd2 Ne7 $5 $146 {[%cal Gc8f5] s} 12. g4 $1 {Necessary pawn sacrifice.} Bxe5 13. fxe5 Nxg4 14. Nf3 f6 15. h3 fxe5 $1 {looks nice, but most probably it will lead to a draw:} 16. hxg4 exd4 17. Bxh7+ $1 {The forced line begins:} Kxh7 18. Ng5+ Kg6 19. Rxf8 Qg3+ 20. Kh1 $1 Bxg4 21. Qf1 $1 Nf5 22. Rxa8 Qh4+ $11 {[%cal Gh1g1,Gh4g3] Draw.} 23. Kg1 Qg3+ 24. Qg2 Qe1+ 25. Kh2 Qe5+ $1 $11) 9... Nc6 10. Bg5 h6 11. Bh4 g5 $1 {[%csl Bg5] s A few months later, GM Shirov improved over the game.} (11... b5 $6 {Abasov played b5, but after:} 12. Re1 $1 $14 {[%csl Ge1] White had a serious advantage.}) 12. Bg3 Bxg3 13. fxg3 Nh5 $1 {[%csl Bh5] Precise reaction.} 14. Kh2 Qd6 15. Ne5 Nxg3 $1 {[%csl Bg3] This semi-forced line is important to know.} 16. Kxg3 f6 17. Na3 fxe5 18. Nb5 Rxf1 19. Qh5 $3 {[%csl Bh5] And as all the beautiful lines in chess, it ends in a repetition:} Qf6 20. Rxf1 Qxf1 21. Qg6+ $11 {[%cal Gg8f8,Gg6h6] Grandelius-Shirov, Olympiad 2024.}) (6. dxc5 {t Harmless line.} Bxc5 {[%csl Gc5] Black develops in one tempo.} 7. O-O O-O 8. Nc3 (8. Bg5 $6 {t is met with the standard reaction:} h6 $1 {[%csl Bh6][%cal Bg7g5,Rg5h4,Gf6e4,Rh4g3] followed by g5 and Ne4.} 9. Bh4 g5 $1 {[%csl Bg5] Key point.} 10. Bg3 Ne4 $15 {Black is just slightly better.}) 8... h6 $1 {[%cal Rc1g5] To stop Bg5.} 9. h3 Nc6 10. Bf4 Re8 $11 {We are following Adams-Bluebaum, EU-chT 2023. Black had no problems.}) 6... c4 $1 {[%csl Bc4] Necessary tempo, to not allow dxc5.} 7. Re1+ {The most critical line.} (7. Be2 {[%csl Re2] t} Nc6 8. b3 cxb3 9. axb3 Bd6 $5 {[%csl Gd6] Black can develop the bishop to d6, a more active square.} 10. c4 $5 {[%csl Gc4] White tries to grab more space.} (10. Bg5 {t Rare option.} h6 11. Bh4 O-O 12. c3 {[%cal Gb3b4,Gb1d2,Gd2b3] White has a long term plan to use the better structure, and create a bind, but it's too slow.} Re8 13. Nbd2 Bf5 14. b4 {can be met with:} g5 $1 $146 {[%csl Bg5] s} 15. Bg3 a5 $5 {Not the only option.} (15... Rc8 $5 {[%cal Rd2b3,Gf6e4] also good enough.} 16. Re1 a6 $11 {Equal.}) 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. bxa5 Rxa5 $11 {[%csl Bg5] The pawn on g5 is not weakening, there is no way to use it.}) 10... O-O 11. Nc3 h6 $1 {[%csl Gh6][%cal Rc1g5] t Good prophylaxis move.} 12. cxd5 Nb4 13. Ne5 {We can follow the game:} Nbxd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bc4 Be6 16. Qf3 Bb4 17. Qg3 {So far everything logical.} Nc3 $5 $146 {[%csl Bc3] Forced line.} (17... Kh8 {Abasov's move is also fine.} 18. Ra2 a5 19. Re2 Qb6 $11 {And very soon, it was a completely equal position. Nepomniachtchi-Abasov, Candidates 2024.}) 18. Bxh6 Qf6 19. Bg5 Bxc4 $1 {[%csl Rg1,Rg3][%cal Rc3e2] Using the fork.} 20. Rae1 $1 {Best move.} Qf5 21. bxc4 Ne4 $1 {And the game soon ends in a repetition:} 22. Rxe4 Qxe4 23. Bf6 Qh7 24. Nd7 Rfe8 25. Bxg7 $5 {[%csl Bg7] Cute tactic.} Qxg7 26. Nf6+ $1 {[%csl Gf6,Rg8][%cal Gf6d7] The king cannot escape the checks.} Kf8 27. Nd7+ Kg8 28. Nf6+ $11 {Draw by repetition.}) 7... Be7 8. Bf1 O-O 9. b3 $1 {The only challenging move.} (9. Bg5 $6 {t is just a waste of tempo.} Nc6 10. b3 $6 {could be a bit late already!} h6 $1 {[%csl Gh6] Useful inclusion.} 11. Bh4 Bg4 $1 {[%csl Rd4] White has problems with the d4 pawn.} 12. c3 b5 $15 {Black is slightly better.}) (9. Nc3 $6 {t Wrong development.} Nc6 10. b3 Bb4 $1 {[%csl Rc3] The knight is misplaced.} 11. Bd2 Bg4 $15 {Serious advantage.}) 9... cxb3 10. axb3 Nc6 {Before engines were strong, the human opinion was that White's structure is potentially slightly better, but now, it is absolutely clear that White has no way to pose any problems to Black!} 11. Ne5 {Most common.} (11. h3 $5 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Gh3g4] t Useful move.} Bf5 12. c3 (12. Bd3 {[%cal Gd1d3,Gc2c4] t} Ne4 $1 {[%csl Be4] is a good reply, we are following Nepo-Erigaisi, 2025.} 13. c3 Re8 $1 $36 {Improvement over the game, Black is doing more than fine.}) (12. c4 {t Most common.} Bb4 $5 {[%csl Bb4] Good reaction.} 13. Bd2 a5 $11 {With a balanced position.}) 12... Re8 $5 {Useful move.} 13. Bf4 h6 $5 $146 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gf5h7] Another prophylactic move.} 14. Nbd2 a6 15. b4 Rc8 {Black has a hidden nuance:} 16. Qb3 (16. Nb3 $2 {fails to:} Nxb4 $1 $17 {[%csl Rb3,Cb4,Gc8,Rd1][%cal Gf5c2,Yc3b4] Typical tactic.}) 16... Bd6 $11 {Balanced position.}) (11. c3 {t} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Bg4] The pin is annoying, that's why usually White starts with 11.h3.} 12. Bf4 Bd6 $11) 11... Ne4 $5 {[%csl Be4] We can jump as well.} 12. Nxc6 bxc6 {No need to worry about the pawn structure here, Black has good pieces.} 13. Bd3 (13. f3 {t} Ng5 $11 {Normal position.}) 13... f5 $1 {[%csl Gf5] To support the knight.} 14. Ba3 {Most logical.} (14. f3 $2 {t Too slow.} Bd6 $1 $17 {[%csl Rg1,Rh2][%cal Gd8h4] Black has a lot of threats.}) 14... Bxa3 15. Nxa3 Qh4 {[%csl Ge4,Gh4] Good activity.} 16. Qe2 a5 $11 {Equal position.} *

