1. e4 {t} e6 2. d3 {King's Indian Attack.} (2. Qe2 {[%cal Ge2e8,Rd7d5] t} c5 $1 {The best way to fight for an advantage.} 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 g6 $1 {easiest way.} 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 $1 {It is important to avoid Nf6 because of e5 later.} 7. c3 e5 $5 {[%csl Be5][%cal Rd2d4] It's better to stop the push on d4 as soon as possible.} (7... O-O {It is less precise because of:} 8. d4 $1 {the most energetic response.} (8. Rd1 $6 {Not the most accurate move due to:} e5 $1 $132 {[%csl Gc5,Ge5] Transpose in line 7...and 8.Rd1.}) 8... cxd4 9. cxd4 Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxd4 11. Rd1 Nc6 (11... Bg7 {Avoiding Bh6.} 12. Nc3 $44 {[%cal Gc1f4,Ge4e5] White is preferable due to better development. There is full compensation.}) 12. Bh6 Re8 (12... Bg7 $5 {[%csl Bg7] Jobava's recommendation.}) 13. Nc3 $44 {It is not easy for Black to free himself from the pressure.}) 8. d3 (8. Rd1 $6 {t} O-O {[%cal Gd7d5]} 9. Na3 d5 $1 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. d3 h6 12. Nc4 Re8 13. a4 b6 $15 {This is the Deac-Kramnik match, 2023 where Black got a good advantage which led to victory later.}) 8... O-O 9. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] popular continuation.} (9. Na3 b6 $132 {[%csl Bb6][%cal Gd7d5] Useful move. Later we will decide when it's the best moment to push d5.}) 9... d5 10. b4 b6 $5 {[%csl Bb6] useful move.} 11. exd5 Nxd5 $15) 2... d5 3. Nd2 (3. Qe2 {t An interesting idea to confuse Black who now already has the pawn on d5 and it would not be good to push to c5 with this move order.} Nc6 4. Nf3 e5 $1 {[%csl Be5] A good practical idea, Black remains faithful to the usual plan.} 5. exd5 (5. g3 {t Black gets a good game after:} Bg4 6. c3 f6 $1 7. Bg2 Qd7 $15 {[%cal Ge8c8]}) 5... Qxd5 6. Nc3 Qa5 {[%csl Re2] GM Bluebaum used to play it in some games, and it is an improved version of the Scandinavian.} 7. g3 (7. Bd2 {t} Bg4 {[%cal Gg4e2,Gc6d4]} 8. Qe4 {This is the Nakamura-Bluebaum blitz match, 2024 and black could have gained a big advantage after:} Nf6 $1 $146 9. Qc4 Bxf3 10. gxf3 Nd4 $17 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gb7b5]}) 7... Bb4 8. Bd2 Bg4 {[%cal Gg4e2,Gc6d4]} 9. Bg2 Nd4 10. Qd1 (10. Qxe5+ {t A possibility but Black gets a small advantage afterwards.} Qxe5+ 11. Nxe5 Nxc2+ 12. Kf1 Nxa1 13. Nxg4 Nc2 14. Bxb7 Rd8 $36 {White compensation is to be demonstrated and Black is preferable.}) 10... Nf6 11. O-O O-O {s And now for example:} 12. a3 Bxc3 13. Bxc3 Qb6 14. Bxd4 exd4 15. Qd2 Rfe8 $11) 3... Nf6 {The most common way for Black.} 4. Ngf3 Nc6 $5 {A simpler way. The idea is to develop quickly with e5, and it doesn't require much theory but an understanding of typical ideas.} (4... c5 {Black's most common continuation.} 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 {[%cal Ge4e5] I don't really like this for Black, because White plans to continue with e5, and then he has a "long game". For example:} b5 9. e5 {The main continuation.} (9. exd5 {This move is also possible.} Nxd5 10. c4 {After this move there is a rather forced sequence:} bxc4 11. dxc4 Ndb4 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gb4d3] s} 12. Ne5 {[%cal Gg2a8]} Bb7 13. a3 Nxe5 14. Bxb7 Nbd3 $1 {[%csl Re1]} 15. Bxa8 Nxe1 16. Qxe1 Nd3 $1 17. Qe3 Nxc1 18. Rxc1 Qxa8 $11 {There have been two games played with this position between Korpa and Kaczur, with both matches ending in a draw.}) 9... Nd7 10. Nf1 $1 {[%cal Gc1f4]} a5 11. h4 a4 12. a3 $1 $40 {[%cal Gf1h2,Gh2g4,Gh4h5,Gc1f4] Stopping Black's expansion on the queenside and only then creating a strong attack on the kingside. In practical play, White has simpler plans to follow, and Black must know exactly what to do to avoid being mated on the kingside.}) 5. c3 {White's second most common move.} (5. g3 $6 {t is the main move but Black always plays for the push on e5 gaining a slight advantage.} dxe4 6. dxe4 Bc5 7. Bg2 e5 $1 {[%csl Be5]} 8. O-O O-O 9. c3 a5 $15 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gf8d8,Gb7b6,Gc8a6,Gh7h6,Gc8e6,Rb2b4] After completing the development Black's position will be more harmonious and therefore preferable.}) (5. e5 {t} Nd7 6. d4 {[%csl Rc8] White takes a lot of space so Black must activate quickly with the classic breaking push:} f6 $1 {[%csl Bf6]} 7. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5e8] Putting pressure on the diagonal.} (7. exf6 $6 {t Many strong players have chosen this move, including Bacrot, but it is not the best continuation.} Qxf6 8. c3 Bd6 9. Bb5 O-O 10. Nf1 {This is the game Bacrot-Goryachkina, 2020 and now:} e5 $1 $17 {It would have gotten a big advantage.}) 7... fxe5 8. dxe5 Be7 9. O-O O-O {[%csl Re5]} 10. Re1 {Only move.} (10. Qe2 $2 {t A big mistake because of:} a6 $1 $17 {[%csl Rb5] And Black manages to gain the pair of bishops.}) 10... Qe8 $5 {[%cal Ge8h5] There are other possibilities but this idea of ​​ctivating the queen seems effective.} 11. Nb3 (11. c4 $2 {t White would do better to prefer development.} a6 $1 12. Ba4 Nc5 $1 {[%csl Ra4] If White now wants to save the bishop, it is too far behind in development.} 13. Bc2 dxc4 14. Nxc4 b5 $1 $19 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Gc6b4,Gc8b7] Followed by Nb4 and Bb7 with clear advantage.}) 11... a6 12. Bf1 Qh5 $15 {[%csl Re5] White has problems defending the e5-pawn and finishing the development.}) 5... Bd6 {[%cal Ge6e5] We can also start from e5 and then Bd6 without much difference.} (5... e5 6. Be2 Bd6 7. O-O O-O 8. exd5 {It was Amin Bassem's choice against Caruana at the 2021 World Blitz Championship but Black had a simple game after that:} (8. b4 {Another possible move but Black gets a good game after:} Ne7 9. Qc2 Ng6 $36 {[%cal Gc7c6,Ga7a5] Black could create strategic problems for White after a5.}) 8... Nxd5 9. Nc4 Re8 10. a4 Bf8 11. a5 a6 $11 {Black could follow up with b6 or b5 or simply with Bf5, in any case the position remains solid.} (11... b5 $5 $146 {Another good possibility.} 12. axb6 cxb6 $36 {[%csl Ga7,Rb2,Gb6,Rc3][%cal Gc8b7,Gf7f6,Gc8e6] Black has more space and the pieces coordinate better.})) 6. g3 (6. Be2 {t Transpose to the line 5...e5.} e5 $132) 6... O-O 7. Bg2 (7. b4 {t Trying to be fast in the expansion but Black has no problems after:} dxe4 8. dxe4 a5 $1 {Trying to weaken White's position.} (8... e5 $5 $132 {As usual this move is part of the plan and therefore possible.}) 9. b5 Ne5 $15 {In the future Black could push to e5 and bring the bishop to c5 by exploiting the weakness caused by the White pawns on the queenside.}) 7... a5 {[%csl Ga5][%cal Rb2b4]} 8. O-O dxe4 $1 {An important inclusion to block the bishop on g2.} (8... e5 $6 {Inaccurate due to:} 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nc4 $14 {[%cal Gg2a8] In this position White is preferable thanks to the free g2 bishop.}) 9. dxe4 (9. Nxe4 {t Possible but even in this case Black's plan remains to block on e5.} Nxe4 10. dxe4 e5 $11 {[%csl Be5][%cal Gf7f6,Gc8e6,Gd8e7] Black finishes developing easily and f6 is an extra option that can be useful.}) 9... e5 $1 $11 {[%csl Re4,Be5,Rg2][%cal Gh7h6,Gc8e6] Usual idea to block Bg2 and better control the center. Black has a comfortable game after simple development moves.} *

