1. e4 {t} e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3 {this provocative move has been played in almost 15K games.} (3. e5 {t} c5 {White can transpose to the 3.e5 French, but other options are also possible.} 4. c3 (4. b4 $6 {t} cxb4 5. a3 (5. d4 {t} Qa5 $15 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gc8d7,Ga8c8] Bd7-Nc6-Rc8 next with a nice queenside play, and Black is better.}) 5... Bd7 $5 {[%csl Gd7] Bd7 is always useful, and we cut a lot of theory.} 6. axb4 (6. d4 {t} Qa5 $15 {[%cal Gb8c6,Ga8c8] Nc6-Rc8 next.}) 6... Bxb4 7. c3 Ba5 {our next moves will be Ne7-Nc6:} 8. d4 Nc6 9. Bd3 Nge7 10. O-O b5 $1 {[%cal Gb5b4] we are ready for b4.} (10... O-O $4 {would be a huge blunder because of} 11. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 12. Ng5+ $18) (10... h6 11. Nh4 $132 {[%cal Gd1g4] Qg4 next, and the game becomes sharp.}) 11. Bxb5 $146 {White's best try.} (11. Ba3 {t} b4 12. cxb4 Bxb4 $15 {[%cal Ga7a5] a5 next.}) 11... Nxe5 $1 12. Nxe5 Bxb5 13. c4 $1 {engine's concrete idea.} dxc4 14. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 15. Qh5+ g6 16. Qxb5 Bb6 {s White has compensation, but no more, for example:} 17. Qxc4 Qxd4 18. Qa6 Rhc8 $132) 4... Nc6 (4... d4 $5 {possible extra option, but no need to go for it.}) 5. g3 {has been recently tried by Carlsen and Jospem.} (5. d4 {transposes to the French Advance Variation.}) 5... f6 {I like this simple solution, and we are following Erigaisi.} 6. d4 (6. exf6 $6 {t} Nxf6 7. d4 $2 {Carlsen-Erigaisi.} cxd4 $1 8. cxd4 Bb4+ $17 {[%cal Gd8b6,Ge8g8] Qb6-00 next.}) 6... cxd4 7. cxd4 fxe5 8. Nxe5 (8. dxe5 {t} Bc5 $15 {[%cal Gg8e7,Ge8g8] Nge7-00 next.}) 8... Bb4+ 9. Nc3 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Ne7 $132 {[%cal Ge8g8] 00 next. Black is doing great and we have easy play.}) (3. d3 {t} dxe4 4. dxe4 Qxd1+ 5. Kxd1 {[%csl Gc7] compared to the Caro Kann, our pawn is on c7 and it means that we can play} Nc6 $132 {[%csl Rd1][%cal Gc8d7,Ge8c8] Bd7-000 next, and we have a very good endgame because White's king on d1 is misplaced.}) (3. exd5 exd5 4. d4 {Transposes in the French Exchange.}) 3... d4 {I think that it makes sense to go for d4, preventing White from playing d2-d4 himself.} 4. Ne2 c5 {In this position, White should play something concrete like b4 or c3, because the slow King's Indian style play doesn't work well with the knight on e2.} 5. c3 {critical continuation.} (5. g3 $6 {[%csl Re2] Ne2 is misplaced.} Nc6 6. Bg2 e5 7. d3 {you can play this position as you wish, but I like the following continuation:} f6 $5 8. O-O g5 $15 {[%csl Gg5] We take space on the kingside, and our position can only be better.}) (5. b4 a6 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6] we prepare Nc6.} (5... Nc6 {I don't like it immediately because White can play} 6. b5 $14) 6. bxc5 Bxc5 7. Bb2 Nc6 {White has nothing better than} 8. c3 dxc3 9. Bxc3 Nf6 10. d4 (10. Ng3 e5 $1 $15 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd8e7] 00-Qe7 next.}) 10... Bb4 11. Bxb4 Nxb4 $15 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gd8a5,Gc8d7,Ga8c8,Ge8g8] e4 is hanging, and we can continue with Qa5-Bd7-Rc8-00.}) 5... Nf6 $1 {This is a very important move to remember.} (5... dxc3 $6 {would be a positional mistake:} 6. bxc3 Nc6 7. Ng3 $14) (5... Nc6 $6 6. cxd4 cxd4 7. Qa4 $1 $14 {Black faces problems.}) 6. e5 (6. cxd4 {t} cxd4 7. Nexd4 (7. e5 Nfd7 {transposes in 6.e5.}) 7... Nxe4 {Black is doing great. The only sensible try for White would be} 8. Nxe6 Bxe6 9. Qa4+ Nc6 {s} 10. Qxe4 {but Black has more than compensation here after many continuations, for example:} Bc5 (10... Qd5 $5 11. Qxd5 Bxd5 $44 {[%cal Ge8c8] 000 next.}) 11. Bc4 O-O 12. O-O (12. Bxe6 $6 Re8 $15 {[%csl Re1]}) 12... Re8 13. d3 h6 $44) (6. Ng3 {t} a6 $1 $15 {[%cal Rf1b5,Gb8c6] we stop Bb5 and are ready to play Nc6 next.} (6... Nc6 {allows} 7. Bb5 $132)) (6. d3 {t} Nc6 $15 {[%csl Re2][%cal Ge6e5] e5 next and White is worse because Ne2 is misplaced.}) 6... Nfd7 7. cxd4 cxd4 8. Nexd4 Nxe5 $1 {Black's key idea.} 9. Bb5+ (9. Nxe5 {t doesn't make sense:} Qxd4 10. Bb5+ Nd7 11. Qe2 a6 $15) 9... Nec6 {[%csl Rb8] our only problem is the strange-looking knight on b8, but I will show you how to solve this issue.} 10. O-O (10. Nxc6 {t is very harmless:} Nxc6 11. O-O Bd7 12. d4 Be7 $11) 10... Bd7 {this is more interesting than 10.Nxc6 because White can try to keep the knights by playing Nb3, Ne2 or Nc2.} 11. Ne2 (11. Nc2 {t} Nb4 $1 $11 {[%cal Gb8c6] we want to exchange the knights so that our Nb8 can comfortably develop on c6.}) (11. Nb3 {t} Na5 $11 {same strategy described in the 11.Nc2 note.}) 11... Bd6 $11 {[%cal Gc6e7] Ne7 next, and our knights will make sense again.} *

